column168: A van arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste.  During check in procedure, it was noticed that material was leaking.  The trailer was placed into the containment area and a response crew was summoned.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment they entered the trailer and found the leaking drum.  It was overpacked into a suitable salvage container.  The trailer floor and affected area of the ground was cleaned with a cleaning compound and the clean up material was also placed into the salvage drum.  The incident was reported to the IEPA, incident number H20120800.
column169: A pinhole leak had developed in the side of the drum, caused by rubbing against a metal rib in the side of the trailer.  The origin location was notified and was to discuss with all employees involved in loading trailers the importance of using proper dunnage.

column168: On August 3, 2012 Landstar Inway contacted ERTS to manage a UN1993 release.  ERTS dispatched a network contractor for initial response and remediation.  The network contractor reported that the drums are leaking because of aging and deterioration on the bottom of the drums.  The contractor applied granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and to the ground below. The areas were swept clean and the materials collected.  The three damaged 55 gallon drums were placed in over pack drums and sent into its destination. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

On 08/01/2012, UTCU 483569 was discovered to be leaking materials from the main flange bottom outlet valve assembly. All 8 bolts of the flange were less that tool tight. The bolts were tightened and secured for further transportation.

column168: On August 8, 2012, a Landstar tractor trailer was involved in a multi-vehicle accident resulting in the release of UN1993 Flammable Liquid to the inside of the trailer. Two 55-gallon steel drums of the product had been damaged. No waterways or storm drains were impacted by the release. ERTS dispatched Allied International Emergency to the site where they over-packed the two leaking drums and utilized absorbent pads to clean off the drums which were splashed by the material during the incident.

On August 4, 2012 a R&L tractor trailer had an incident where approximately one gallon of UN2051 dimethylaminoethanol was release on the top of the drum at the terminal from  an apparent puncture when the box fell off the pallet. ERTS dispatched HazChem to the site for initial response and remediation. The contractor over packed the drum and staged it onsite to be returned back to the shipper for reclamation/disposition.

The tanker was loaded and the exterior washed down at the Kinder Morgan Facility, the dome lid was not secured and as the truck left the facility if leaked and trailer material down the roadway ending at a Quality Carriers Terminal located at 1045 E. Hazelwood Ave, Rahway, NJ.     Neutralization and cleanup was completed at the Kinder Morgan Facility and along the route the truck to.    All waste will be disposed at a permitted facility.

column168: On August 8, 2012 a Landstar Ligon tractor trailer experienced hard braking incident.  The hard breaking resulted in a load shift that punctured a 275 gallon tote.  The tote released approximately 175 gallons to the trailer floor and soil below. ERTS dispatched a network contractor for clean up.  The contractor unloaded the cargo and worked in granular absorbents to the trailer floor. The 10'x10' area of impacted soil was excavated and backfilled to its original condition. The remaining product in the damaged tote was transferred into a new tote and sent along to the destination. The trailer was decontaminated and the remaining 13 totes were placed back on the trailer.  All generated waste was placed into a roll off container and transported off site for pending disposal.
Drums were protected with plywood and in the process of unloading the plywood was moved. Forklift mishandling resulted in blades puncturing the drum, causing the leak. Clean up in house.
column169: Forklift retraining of employee.

column168: 8/16/2012 11:56:11 AM Con-Way contacted ERTS concerning the release of a UN2810 Toxic Liquid 8/16/2012 11:56:11 AM Organic located at terminal ULB in Long Beach, California. Approximately 1/2 gallon of material was released to the trailer floor from a tote onboard. ERTS is coordinating a response with a network contractor and will provide an ETA once made available.    8/16/2012 1:23:38 PM The contractor is onsite at this time and will begin investigating the release momentarily. ERTS has notified the California Emergency Management Agency and were assigned report number 12-4837 to this incident.     8/16/2012 2:14:11 PM The contractor has reported that two totes containing the UN 2810 product have leaked a minimal amount of material to the trailer floor and sides of the totes. The contractor has reported that the totes seem intact and do not need to be transferred but they will offload them to inspect them more closely. The contractor will then secure the caps and perform the necessary cleanup with absorbents and absorbent pads.     8/16/2012 4:47:01 PM The contractor has reported that the leaks were due to missing gaskets and faulty caps on the totes. The contractor has completed the necessary cleanup and resecured the caps and new gaskets on first tote. The contractor has partially finished the cleanup of the second tote but they need to offload it in order to complete the proper cleanup and resecure the cap and new gaskets.     8/16/2012 5:50:22 PM The contractor has completed the cleanup at this time and is departing the site. One drum of material was staged at the terminal to be handled by Con-Way personnel.

column168: On August 3, 2012, at 1129 hours, FRA Inspector Richard Ingram discovered GATX 79813, a residue tank car of Methanol, releasing vapors from the top of the car in CSXTs Milan Yard.  The car was isolated and shipper, Invista SARL, was contacted via CHEMTREC report #2012-08-03-00118.  Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 3 of 4 liquid line valve mounting flange bolts/nuts less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Invistas representative, Joaquin Mercado at 613-340-2891.  Contractor personnel tightened the loose bolts/nuts with a wrench to secure the container.  The liquid line valve mounting flange area was then checked for leaks with a soapy water solution.  No exceptions were noted and the rail car was released to destination.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    NARRI 5x(4+3+0) x (2+0) =  70  Cause Code: 270
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On August 4, 2012, at 1215 hours, an FRA inspector at the CSXT Manville yard noticed an odor escaping from GATX 300472, a residue tank car of UN1993, Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. (Acetone, Toluene). The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Veolia Technical Solutions, was notified directly via the provided emergency contact phone number. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the Manville yard and  found one of the six manway swing bolts less than tool tight. Additionally a nozzle gasket was found in a deteriorated state and a ring gasket was the incorrect size and not in the gasket groove. Hepaco replaced the gaskets with an EPDM nozzle type gasket and tightened the manway bolt appropriately. The shipper representative, Tim, was notified of the situation found. The vapor release was secured and GATX 300472 was released for disposition.  This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(4+3+1)x(2+0) = 80  Cause codes: 209 + 212
column169: No additional comments.

column168: During loading of cargo from warehouse to agent’s assigned trucking company, forklift operator punctured one drum and while doing so, another drum fell. Area was immediately cordoned off.  Warehouse staff was evacuated from facility.  At this time the local Operators SOP was followed which states to contact Fire Department, Police Department, Emergency Response for Haz Mat, Management of airline, and management of facility.  Fire and Police arrived surveyed the scene, recognized no persons were in immediate danger, confirmed to evacuate facility, and stated to await haz mat clean up team.  Haz Mat clean up team arrived at 2035 hrs, 5 hours after the initial call.  Clean up took place which included forklift, warehouse floor, truck, remaining skids that were impacted, and removal of both damaged drums and the wood skid that carried the drums.
column169: New and updated forklift training will take place for my handling companies staff.  In addition the storage process will be reviewed.

column168: THERE WAS A STONG ODOR WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED.  THE DOCKWORKER, INBOUND SUPERVISOR AND INBOUND CLERK ENTERED THE TRAILER TO FIND OUT WHAT WAS CAUSING THE ODOR. THE THREE EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THAT AFTERNOON.  THE HOSPITAL TOLD THEM THE TOXIC FUMES WOULD BE OUT OF THIER SYSTEM IN AN HOUR OR SO AND THERE SHOULD NOT BE ANY LONG TERM AFFECTS.  THE HAZMAT FREIGHT WAS WEDGED BETWEEN ANOTHER SHIPMENT AND THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE WAS SATURATED.  THE BOX MAY HAVE BEEN DROPPED PRIOR TO LOADING AS THE BOX WAS TILTED SLIGHTLY BUT STILL HAD THE ORIENTATION ARROWS POINTING UP INDICATING THE BOX DID NOT MOVE MUCH DURING TRANSIT.

column168: AN IRREG SORTER NOTICED A PUDDLE BEGINNING TO FORM AROUND A HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT HAD FALLEN APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET OFF THE IRREG BELT NEAR DOOR 193.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR, CODY.  CODY CALLED FOR THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS & LET US KNOW OF THE LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE.  WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE / RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NO CHANGES TO MY PPE WERE NECESSARY. column168: On August 1, 2012, Pitt Ohio contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions concerning the referenced incident.  ERTS dispatched Environmental Management Specialist and SunPro to the site to perform cleanup activities.  It was discovered that the referenced material was released from the referenced container due to a possible open valve and/or broken cap on the discharge valve.  Evidence of the released material first began at the interchange of Interstate 94 and Interstate 69 in Marshall, Michigan.  The material was released along Interstate 69 South into Indiana and onto Interstate 80 East at Milepost 144 in Fremont, Indiana.  Material was released to Interstate 80 East into Ohio where the tractor trailer came to a stop on Interstate 80 East Milepost 13 in Holiday City, Ohio.  Environmental Management Specialist performed the necessary cleanup in Ohio.  SunPro performed the necessary cleanup in Indiana.  No cleanup was required by the Michigan DOT.

Trailer overfilled while driver was loading at well site. Driver was in the cab of the tractor doing paperwork when he witnessed liquid coming from the trailer vent.  driver exited the cab and shut down the loading process. Driver put out spill pads and contacted his dispatch.
column169: Driver was aware of his responsibilities for attending the loading of his trailer. Driver failed to follow company policy and procedures. Driver was placed off work pending disciplinary action per company policy including retraining.

column168: A van trailer at the intermediate truck transfer facility was being unloaded for the consolidation of shipments to various intended waste disposal facilities.  During this process, a drum was found to have some liquid puddled on the lid.  The liquid did not go the the floor of the trailer.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the supervisor placed absorbent pads onto the top of the drum, blotting up all of the liquid.  The leaking drum and absorbent pads were then overpacked into a suitable salvage container.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column168: Tank car UTLX 205376, in the railyard, was reported with a fresh product stain on its side shell that emanated from its top fitting area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were immediately notified and inspected UTLX 205376. Intact seal SUNOCO 012714 was removed from the valve housing cover. Detailed inspection revealed the leak source was at the liquid valve's operating valve stem assembly at the valve body. The valve stem's two bolt packing gland/retainer plate was loose with one nut/washer combination not applied on the bolt stud as they were lying at the base of the valve body. The responders applied the washer and nut, and then tool tightened both nuts on the bolt studs for the packing gland/retainer plate. After this securement was completed, no further product release was observed with all spillage evaporating.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels.They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: The release of approximately 200 gallons of solvent naphtha occurred at a rail terminal located at 601 N Hoskins Rd, Charlotte, NC 28216. The terminal is owned by TRANSFLO Terminal Services, Inc (TRANSFLO), and operated by KMMS. The release occurred during a railcar to truck trailer trans-load at approximately 10:35 a.m. on  August 2, 2012. The release was discovered by KMMS operator, David McKenzie, who was in charge of the transfer. Mr. McKenzie was scheduled to transfer 1,400 gallons of solvent naphtha into a 1,500 gallon compartment on the truck trailer via metered platform pump. The release of approximately 200 gallons was due to a failed alarm on the high level probe. The alarm had been inadvertently turned off during a training exercise. The operator was standing approximately 25 feet away from the platform pump discussing transloading operations to a trainee at the time of the release. The release occurred through the dome opening on the truck trailer, down the side of the trailer to impervious asphalt. Once the release was visually observed coming down the side of truck trailer the KMMS operator quickly ascended the platform and shut the transfer down. Mr. McKenzie called a code yellow (chemical release) and terminal employees responded to dam and dike the released solvent naphtha with Absorbal®. Although no reportable quantity was exceeded nor any storm drains or waterways impacted a call was placed the NRC as a best management practice at the request of TRANSFLO. The estimated release volume of 200 gallons was based upon the response time of the operator to shut down the pump (1.67 minutes) and the flow rate of the pump(120 gallons / per minute). A call was placed by KMMS Customer Service Representative, Ms. Cindy Hunsberger, at 10:55 a.m. to the Carolina Emergency Response Team (CERT), a private emergency response company based in Charlotte, NC to clean up the released solvent naphtha. CERT arrived at the terminal at 11:20 a.m. and properly cleaned the spilled material.  Mr. Jeff Mitchell from the Mecklenburg County, NC, Department of Environmental  Protection, Water Division, arrived at the terminal to inspect the release site at 1:05 p.m. and was satisfied with the response and clean-up and that no waterways were impacted.
column169: KMMS is working on corrective measures to prevent reoccurrence including modifying  our operator training program and installing a metered pump that automatically shuts-off at the desired set volume. KMMS is requesting the metered pump from our customer who supplies the required transfer equipment.    In the meantime, KMMS will ensure that in-depth training is conducted during non-critical times.  This will help ensure that focus is not lost and that load is monitored vigilantly.

column168: An end dump trailer loaded with a shipment of hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  After being checked in, he was directed to go to the dumping area of the landfill.  He had loosened his ratchets on the tailgate and assumed the tailgate hooks would hold the tailgate shut.  When he moved forward, the hooks did not hold and the tailgate opened, spilling out the material in the area just away from the scale.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material and took it to the dumping area of the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The driver claimed that the hooks were worn and faulty and did not hold the tailgate securely.  He should not have loosened the ratchets until he arrived in the dumping area.  The driver will receive a written warning when he arrives back at his domicile.

column43: UD ULTRA LSD (S-15PPM) ULTRA LOW SULFUR DIESEL
column168: PENN TANK LINES WAS CONTRACTED TO DELIVER A LOAD OF FUEL TOTALING 7500 GALLONS INTO THIS LOCATION. THE DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED FROM OUR BALTIMORE TERMINAL. ON ARRIVAL AT UNLOADING FACILITY THE DRIVER DETERMINED THAT THE TOTAL GALLONS LOADED WOULD NOT FIT INTO THE FIRST TANK OR THE SECOND TANK BY USE OF THE TANK GAGES.  HE THEN HOOKED HIS PRODUCT HOSE TO THE TANK AND PUMPED A PORTION OF THE LOAD INTO THE FIRST TANK. USING THE TANK GAGE HE KNEW WHEN THE TANK WAS AT THE CORRECT LEVEL SO THAT THE BALANCE OF THE LOADED GALLONS WOULD FIT INTO THE SECOND TANK. ADDITIONALLY THE DRIVER CLIMBED ON TOP OF THE TRAILER AND GAGED THE COMPARTMENT TO DETERMINE THAT PRODUCT LEFT AFTER UNLOADING THE FIRST TANK MATCHED THE ROOM SHOWING AVAILABLE ON THE SECOND TANK. THE DRIVER THROUGH HE HAD CLOSED THE APPROPRIATE VALVE ON FIRST TANK TO THE SECOND TANK WITH THE LINE STILL UNDER PRESSURE THE PRODUCT EXCAPTED FROM THE HOSE.  ON SEEING THE DISCHARGE OF PRODUCT FROM THE DELIVERY HOSE, THE DRIVER REALIZING HIS ERROR IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND BEGAN OPERATION TO CONTAIN THE SPILL USING AVAILABLE SPILL MATERIALS. AFTER THE THE DRIVER SECURED THE AREA HE CALL HIS DISPATCHER MR. DAVID SNOW. MR. SNOW IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE SPILL TO HIS SUPERIORS AND THE COMPANY RISK SUPERVISOR LARRY DALTON. THE DRIVER ALSO NOTIFIED THE ON-DUTY SUPERVISOR FOR ESTES MR. JAMES ABLE. ON NOTIFICATION TO THE COMPANY THE FOLLOWING CALLS WERE MADE TO A SPILL CONTRACTOR AND THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES BY LARRY DALTON. - ACE ENVIRONMENTAL, 3512 FAIRFIELD ROAD, BALTIMORE, MD, 21226, PH. 868-750-4223; - NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER - REPORT NO. 1019679 - PETTY OFFICER ARNSCNAULT; - MARYLAND HAZMAT RESPONSE CENTER - JAY MILLER. ACE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE ARRIVING APPROXIAMTELY 10:00PM. ACE SUPERVISOR OBSERVED THAT THE SPILL APPEARED TO BE ABOUT 30 TO 40 GALLSON AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN THE AREA OF THE SPILL USING STA-DRI & SORBENT PADS. BOOMS WERE ALSO PLACED AROUND THE SPILL IN CASE OF RAIN SHOWERS SO THAT PRODUCT WOULD NOT SPREAD. ON LEAVING SITEACT LEFT BOOMS IN PLACE AROUND SPILL. THE FOLLOWING DAY (THURSDAY 8.13.12) APPROXIMATELY 10:00 HOURS ACE ENVIRONMENTAL RETURNED TO THE SITE OF THE SPILL AND POWER WASHED THE IMPACED AREA WITH SIMPLE GREEN CLEANER POWER WASHER AND VACUUM TRUCK.  USING THE BOOMS LEFT IN PLACE THE PREVIOUS NIGHT ALONG WITH AN ADDITIONAL SET OF BOOMS ALL MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND VACUUMED INTO TRUCK FOR DISPOSAL BY ACE ENVIRONMENTAL. ALL SPILL MATERIALS WERE DRUMMED AND REMOVED FROM SITE.
column169: TERMINAL OPERATIONS TO USE A MULTI-COMPARTMENT TANK FOR LOADS REQUIRING PUMP-OFF'S INTO MORE THAN ONE TANK & VERIFY THE QUANTITY WILL FIT BEFORE SHIPPING.  IF USING A SINGLE COMPARTMENT TANK TERMINAL OPERATIONS TO VERIFY THAT ALL PRODUCT WILL FIT IN ON TANK.  DRIVER TRAINING NEEDS STRENGTHENED ON PUMPING LOADS OFF OF TRAILER TO ENSURE THAT OPERATION OF PUMPS ARE UNDERSTOOD.

column25: ALTIVIA CORPORATION C/O BAYER MATERIAL SCIENCE
column168: DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS THE DELIVERY HOSE BROKE AWAY AT THE COUPLER CONNECTED TO THE CUSTOMERS TANK. WHEN THE DRIVER TRIED TO GRAB THE HOSE HE WAS SPRAYED WITH MATERIAL. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLOSE HIS VALVES AND STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. THE DRIVER WAS THEN TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.
column169: THE INVESTIGATION BY THE CARRIER'S MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT REVEALED THAT THE POLY VINYL COUPLING HAD A HAIR LINE CRACK IN IT, WHICH CAUSED THE COUPLING TO SEPARATE FROM THE HOSE WHEN PRESSURE WAS PUT ON THE HOSE. ALL SIMILAR HOSES IN THAT SERVICE HAVE BEEN PRESSURE TESTED AND THOSE THAT SHOWED ANY SIGNS OF CRACKING WERE REMOVED FROM SERVICE. ALL HOSES PURCHASED IN THE FUTURE FOR THIS WORK WILL BE EQUIPPED WITH PT COUPLER BUMP CAPS TO PREVENT THEM FROM CRACKING SHOULD THE DRIVER DROP THEM ON THE GROUND.

column168: A BNSF roadswitch crew member reported being splashed by product expelled from the top of tank car UTLX 200541 during switching activities at the consignee's (Trimac Transportation Services) industry track location. The splashed BNSF employee was on the ground near UTLX 200541 and immediately washed off impacted skin area. Afterwards, further water washing/decontaminating was initiated by responding EMS personnel. The BNSF employee sustained no reportable injuries. Apparently, unattended UTLX 200541 was in the process of being unloaded by the consignee (Trimac Transportation Services). The manway cover and the liquid line were not secured. Only one of eight manway securement bolts were applied and the liquid line's blind flange closure connection was loose. Movement of UTLX 200541 during a coupling event resulted in the product being expelled from these unsecured top fittings. An unsecured unloading fitting attachment and an adjustable wrench were laying atop UTLX 200541. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder secured the manway closure and the liquid line blind flange closure and removed the unsecured unloading fitting and wrench from UTLX 200541.
column169: Ensure consignee's unloading procedures include total securement of all valves and fittings if a hazardous material transportation package is unattended or not on-site monitored during its unloading process.

column168: On 8/7/2012, a transload operator at the Ft. Lauderdale TRANSFLO terminal was completing a liquid transfer of Ferric Chloride from a railcar to  truck trailer. A product hose was secured to the open dome lid of the trailer and the liquid Ferric Chloride was being splash loaded into the trailer. During the last part of the transfer, the operator was blowing the loading hose clean with air to force the remainder of Ferric Chloride out of the loading hose and into the trailer. As the operator was blowing back product hose into trailer, the pressure from the hose contacted the liquid product in the truck. The liquid level was approximately 4-6" from the end of the product hose that was being blown clean. This sudden release of pressure from the hose cause the liquid in the trailer to splash upward and resulted in was a sudden upward spray of liquid Ferric Chloride from the open dome lid on the trailer. The Ferric Chloride that splashed out of the top dome lid on the trailer ran down the sides of the railcar. Approximately 5 gallons of  Ferric Chloride was released. No storm drains were impacted, but some ferric chloride impacted the soil when it mixed with large water puddles in the yard. The spilled material was cleaned up and properly disposed of.
column169: This was a new additional carrier for this transfer. The regular carrier’s trailer is equipped with bottom load piping for loading where the operator can connect directly to the trailer's piping to utilize cam lock connections. A false dome lid or channel spout was not available for use for this transfer as the regular carrier’s trailer does not require them. Because the trailer was not equipped with bottom load piping to allow for bottom loading; and a false dome lid or channel spout was not available, the operator incorrectly decided to splash load the trailer by securing the product hose to the trailer dome lid. He secured the hose to the trailer by using rubber bungee cords. This was the direct cause of the product release. If a channel spout or false dome lid would have been utilized for this transfer, this incident would not have occurred as the spout or false dome lid would have prevented product from being splashed back out of the dome lid when the product hose was being blown clean.    ROOT CAUSES:   1.Lack of knowledge due to inadequate training of approved loading procedures.  2.Lack of skill due to inadequate review of loading procedures and instructions.  3.Inadequate leadership and/or supervision resulting in inadequate instructions, orientation, and/or training.    CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   1.Knowledge and skill training: Review, train, and test all employees on the approved loading procedures for railcar to trailer transfers of Ferric Chloride.  2.Order a channel spout for Ferric Chloride transfers and require use of channel spout on all ferric chloride transfers when bottom loading is not possible or recommended.   3. Splash loading using bungee cords or ropes to secure the product hose to the trailer dome lid is strictly prohibited for any transfers of any liquid products.

column168: AT 1540 ON SATURDAY, AUGUST 11, 2012 A CREW MEMBER ON THE BROWNVILLE JCT SWITCHER SMELLED AMMONIA WHILE WORKING AROUND PROX 32378 RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE CREW MEMBER REPORTED THE SMELL TO THE RAIL TRAFFIC CONTROLLER IN HERMON, MAINE AND WAS TOLD TO EVACUATE THE AREA AND PROCEED TO THE EAST END OF BROWNVILLE JCT YARD. INITIALLY THE BROWNSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED FOLLOWED BY THE PENOBSCOT COUNTY HAZ-MAT EMERGENCY TEAM AND MAINE DEP. ON ARRIVAL THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS EVALUATED THE SITUATION AND FOUND NO VAPOR AROUND THE CAR. FOLLOWING INITIAL EVALUATION A FOUR MAN TEAM SUITED IN LEVEL B MOUNTED THE CAR AND FOUND 8000 PPM (PIP FACTOR DIFFERENTIAL INCLUDED) READINGS OUTSIDE THE DOME AND 26440 PPM READINGS INSIDE THE DOME. THE VAPOR VALVE WAS TIGHTENED 1/4 TO 1/2 TURN BY HAND AND 1/4 TURN BY WRENCH. THE PLUG MOUNTED ON THE VAPOR VALVE STEM UNDER THE WHEEL WAS ALSO TIGHTEN BETWEEN 1/4 AND 1/2 TURN. READINGS IMMEDIATELY STARTED TO COME DOWN QUICKLY. FURTHER READINGS AFTER INITIAL REMEDIAL ACTION SHOWED 32 TO 120 PPM INSIDE THE DOME CONTINUOUSLY FLUCTUATING INDICATING RESIDUAL VAPOR WAS PRESENT. THE HAZ-MAT TEAM AND DEP FELT THE CAR WAS NO SAFE TO MOVE SO THE CAR WAS RELOCATED TO THE EXTREME WEST END OF BROWNVILLE JCT WHICH IS REMOTE AND MORE THAN 1/2 MILE FROM THE NEAREST RESIDENCE. ON MONDAY, AUGUST 13, 2012 THE DEP AND THREE MMA SUPERVISORS RETURNED TO THE CAR TO RECHECK IT FOR RESIDUAL VAPOR. AIR READINGS AROUND THE CAR AND INSIDE THE DOME WERE "0". IT WAS NOTED BY DEP ON MONDAY, AUGUST 13, 2012 THAT WHEN PLACING THEIR PIP SOLIDLY AND DIRECTLY ON THE INSIDE THREADS OF THE VAPOR LINE PLUG INTO PIPE SEALANT WHICH HAD BEEN APPLIED IN THE PAS THEY WERE ABLE TO OBTAIN A READING OF 28 (EXTREMELY LOW) WHICH COULD VERY WELL BE RESIDUAL LEFT ON THE SEALANT AND EVEN THE CHEMICAL COMPONENTS OF THE PIPE SEALANT ITSELF. NOT DEEMED A HAZARD. READINGS WERE "0" IN DOME.
column169: EVERY VALVE AND PLUG SHOULD BE TIGHTENED TO THE FULLEST EXTENT POSSIBLE AS RECOMMENED BY THE VALVE MANUFACTURES. THIS PROCEDURE SHOULD BE DONE EVEN IF A SPECIFIC POINT WASN'T USED DURING THE PROCESS.

column168: THE DRIVER FILLED THE IBC, AS HE NORMALLY WOULD, AT THE ST. PAUL LOCATION. BUNGS WERE CHECKED AND TIGHT AND THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED WITH A TOTE WRENCH. DURING TRANSIT, A SMALL AMOUNT OF FLUOROSILICIC ACID ESCAPED FROM THE CAP, DUE TO UNDER-TIGHTENING. IT POOLED IN A SMALL DEPRESSION ON TOP OF THE TOTE. NO MATERIAL RAN OFF THE TOTE TO THE FLOOR. THE TINY SPILL WAS WIPED UP WITH A TOWEL AND THE CAP WAS RE-TIGHTENED.
column169: PROPERLY TIGHTENED CAPS WILL NOT LEAK, PROVIDING THE CAP AND GASKET ARE IN GOOD CONDITION. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN TRAINED ON CAP AND GASKET INSPECTION AND HAS HAD PROPER CAP TIGHTENING PROCEDURE DEMONSTRATED TO HIM.

column168: A passing northbound train reported a strong odor emanating from a southbound BNSF train operating on the adjacent main track. The BNSF train was stopped awaiting response from BNSF hazardous material responders and Cowlitz county F.D. Investigation revealed entrained tank car TEIX 2947 had fresh product spillage emanating from its manway closure. Intact seal Canexus 232138 was removed from the manway closure. Responders reported 7 of 8 manway securement bolts were not tool tight and the manway gasket was missing. The responders applied a new manway nozzle gasket and properly secured the manway closure by tool tightening all eight manway securement bolts. Seal BNSF 001386 was applied at the manway closure. Spillage on the tank shell was evaporating and no ground spillage was observed.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  The tractor-tanker unit was involved in a single vehicle accident as a result of an undetermined cause.  As a result of the accident, the tanker was damaged resulting in a release of approximately 6600 gallons of free liquid.  The free liquid impacted a roadside ditch.  Environmental Management, Inc. was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Environmental Management, Inc. arrived and completed a site assessment.  Environmental Management, Inc. determined that most of the free liquids were contained to a 30 x 40 foot area.  Environmental Management, Inc. deployed absorbent material as needed.  Republic Carriers personnel recovered the remaining liquids from the tanker.  Environmental Management, Inc. excavated the contaminated soil from the impacted area.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: OUTSIDE OF THE BLUE AT DOOR 210, A DRIVER WAS INSPECTING HIS LOADS & NOTICED THAT A HAZMAT PACKAGE AT THE END OF A TRAILER WAS UPSIDE-DOWN & LEAKING. HE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR & THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I USED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED PH TAPE TO TEST THE LIQUID & FOUND THE PH TO BE APPROXIMATELY 12. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID TO A PH BETWEEN 6-9. THEN I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID. I SWEPT UP ALL MATERIALS USED FOR CLEAN-UP & PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE PACKAGE, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE CAPS HAD LEAKED & THAT THE OTHER 3 BOTTLES WERE SOILED BY THE PRODUCT.
column169: TAPE WAS USED TO HOLD CAPS IN PLACE & SO WAS CUSHIONING, THEREFORE I HAVE NO RECOMMENDATIONS AT THIS TIME.

column168: Our trator/trailer was traveling on I-294N when a private vehicle went to switch lanes and struck our unit.  The contact caused our unit to swerve and come to a sudden stop.  The load of batteries shifted forward and 4 batteries were damaged.  Police came to scene and filled out a report.  The driver of the private vehicle was cited for Improper Lane Change.  We hire a HM Response team to clean up the acid that had leaked from the 4 batteries and filed reports with Illinois. No soil, surface water or storm drains were effected by the release. The batteries leaked due to being over-turned and cap coming off.
column169: Possibly increase the blocking and bracing to further decrease the chances of the load from shifting during an accident.

column168: Drums were being loaded at the pick up location. A pallet was placed in the back of the transportation vehicle.  As the drum was being moved from the pallet into place in the truck, the driver noticed that there was a leak coming from the bottom of the conatiner on the side.  The container was laid on its side with the leaking area up. The container was then placed in a spill containement pan removed from the truck and the contents were transferred to another container.  The material leaked appoximatly 4 gallons in the back of the truck.  It ran to the front of the truck and some dripped oto the ground.  The acid was neutralized with sodium bicarbonate and all spill control and neutralization materials were cleaned up and drummed for disposal and continued transportation to disposal facility. The Maryland Department of Environment was notified of the release at 12:45PM with no follow up action required.
column169: A management investigation was conducted and the shipper was advised of the  results and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: LANCS Industries in Kirkland, WA shipped a limited quantity (16 oz) of HH-66 vinyl cement (UN1133, Adhesive, containing a flammable liquid, PG II) by ground to PNNL in Richland WA.  The material is composed of 45.5 wt% MEK, 21.5 wt% acetone, and 19.4 wt% toluene.  The manufacturer's MSDS identifies the flash point as -5.5C (22F) and the boiling point of acetone (the most volatile component) as 132F (56C). The material was in an inner metal can (<0.5 L) within a strong outer, non-specification fiberboard box.  There was no damage to the package and no release of contents.  UPS thermal shipping label identified the presence of "1 can vinyl cement."  There were no markings (no UN#, PSN, black and white square on point, or ORM-D).  Labels and shipping papers are not required per 173.150.

column168: PETRO EXPRESS CO. JAMES MORRIS, LOADED 8500 GALS. OF GASOLINE IN BALTIMORE MD TO DELIVER TO QUEENSTOWN MD. DRIVER WAS MAKING LEFT TURN FROM RT 10 ONTO RT 2 WHEN CARGO TANK (1987 ALLIED #217) BECAME DETACHED FROM POWER UNIT (2007 VOLVO #103). CARGO TANK (#217) LANDED IN RIGHT LANE RT 2 SB AND SLID ONTO SHOULDER OF ROAD APPROX. 20' UNTIL STOPPING AGAINST GUARD RAIL. UNDECARRIAGE INCLUDING FRON FENDER, LANDING LEGS AND LOAD RETENTION PIPING WAS DAMAGED. PRODUCT FROM #2 LOAD RETENTION PIPING (APPROX 3-5 GALS.) WAS RELEASED ONTO ROADWAY. DRIVER DISTRIBUTED ABSORBANT PADS AND CONTAINED THE PRODUCT TO A SMALL AREA OF THE ROAD SHOULDER. ANNE ARUNDEL COUNTY POLICE AND FIRE, ALSO MARYLAND DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENT SPILL RESPONSE UNIT RESPONDED. MDE SPILL RESPONSE PUMPED THE LOAD FROM CARGO TANK (#217) ONTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK UNIT THAT DELIVERED THE LOAD TO ITS DESTINATION. CARGO TANK (#217) WAS TOWED TO BALTIMORE CARGO TANK SERVICES FOR REPAIRS. ANNE ARUNDEL COUNTY SPECIAL OPERATIONS DIVISION INSPECTED POWER UNIT (#103) AND DETERMINED LOWER COUPLER PLATE (5TH WHEEL) LATCHING MECHANISM MALFUNCTIONED. PETRO EXPRESS CO. SAFETY DEPT. RECOVERED ABSORBANT PADS, APPLIED ABSORBANT (STAY DRI) TO REMOVE RESIDUE FUEL FROM ASPHALT ON SHOULDER OF ROAD.

column168: The driver of the vehicle was stopped for the night at a truck stop.  While completing his routine pretrip inspection, he noticed a small amount of liquid had leaked from the tailgate of the box onto the fender.  A response crew was called, and upon arrival donned the appropriate personal protective equipment  and began solidifying the material.  This was a sludge material that had separated some liquid during transportation.  The material was solidified to a point where it no longer leaked any liquid and the driver departed to the intended waste disposal facility with no further incident.
column169: The shipper was notified and advised they would check their process to see why there was still too much liquid content in the material.  The material appeared dry when picked up.

column168: A van trailer was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for the contents to be consolidated into other trailers destined for various locations.  While unloading a pallet of drums with the forklift, a drum toppled off and hit the side of the trailer, causing a gash in the side of the drum which began leaking.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The spilled material on the trailer floor and ground underneath was cleaned up with an absorbent material.  All cleanup materials were also placed into the salvage drum.  The drum was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The dock worker who was unloading the drum was cautioned to slow down and use caution when unloading pallets of unsecured drums.

column168: A rolloff box arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  At time of check in, a small leak was discovered coming from the rear door.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up what had spilled onto the ground with absorbent pads.  The load was immediately sampled and taken into the plant for processing along with the spill pads.
column169: The gasket on the rear door was faulty.  It had a tear in it and had begun to deteriorate.  The box was taken to the maintenance facility for repair before being placed back in service.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Here is the narrative of what happened that morning. At approximately 7:30 AM our driver noticed that there was liquid on the ground below his trailer while conducting a Pre Trip inspection on his truck. He discovered that a drum of Sodium Hypochlorite Solution 12.5% on the trailer was leaking upon closer inspection.  The driver observed a small hole in the drum that was responsible for the release.  In the process of the driver removing the drum from the pallet it was on there was a loss of 10 - 20 gallons of Sodium Chlorite inside the trailer.  The Sodium Chlorite inside the trailer and the soil below the trailer was cleaned up using absorbent.  The absorbent and leaking drum were placed into a 95 gallon overpack drum for proper disposal.  The Climate conditions were sunny and approximately 75 degrees F.  There were no injuries, road closures, evacuations or release toa storm drain as a result of the incident.
column169: No Recommendations were made because the cause of the failure is unclear.

column168: When the driver pulled into a DOT scale location, it was discovered that there was some product crystalized on the outside of the trailer. One of the washout caps on top of the cargo tank was missing.  The driver had inspected everything during his pretrip and everything was tight with no signs of leakage.  It's possible that the cap was cross threaded and eventually worked loose.  An environmental response team was dispatched to clean up the side of the cargo tank.  It is estimated that 1 gallon had spilled out. driver obtained another cap to replace the missing one.
column169: Driver was counseled on what to look for on the washout cap and threads and making sure they are not cross-threaded.  A properly secured cap should not come off during transit.

column168: On August 22, 2012, ERTS was contacted by Vitran to oversee environmental cleanup operations stemming from a UN1263 flammable paint release. The release was caused by a 55-gallon drum falling from the trailer. Approximately 15 gallons of product was released to the parking lot with approximately 5 gallons entering a nearby storm drain. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor, Sunpro, to the site for celanup. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted parking lot and the paint was removed from the impacted drain. All waste was collected and containerized for disposal.

column168: On August 15, 2012, a Louisiana Transport tractor trailer suffered a release of UN2735 Amines due to a damaged valve on a tote. The product was released onto the trailer floor and the roadway below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup. The impacted area was neutralized and granular absorbents were applied and worked in thoroughly. The remaining product in the tote was then transferred into a replacement container. All of the waste was collected and containerized for disposal.

Approximately 25 gallons of UN1987 Flammable liquid was released from a damaged 55-gallon drum located on a Dayton Freight trailer. The released product impacted the trailer floor and the asphalt below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted areas and were worked in thoroughly. The waste was collected and containerized for disposal.

column58: Gasket; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column62: Deterioration or Aging; Deterioration or Aging
column168: On August 23, 2012, at 1600 hours at Queensgate Terminal, Cincinnati, OH, a strong odor was reported near WCHX 23123, a loaded tank car of UN1993, Crude Sulfate Turpentine. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Domtar Paper Company LLC, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2012-0823-00213. A CSX hazmat manager found vapors releasing from the pressure relief device (PRD) and covered the PRD with plastic bags to prevent release of vapors. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Representative, Barry Zuercher (270) 222-0269 who contracted a mobile repair shop to inspect and repair the PRD.    On August 24, 2012, a CSX hazmat manager returned to the site to inspect the area around the tank car for vapors. There was still a noticeable odor and it appeared that vapors were emanating from the manway. A new nozzle style manway gasket was then placed on the tank car and the odor dissipated.    On August 31, Rescar, a certified mobile repair shop replaced the "O" rings in the pressure relief device and placed home shop for repairs stickers on both sides of the tank car. The tank car is currently awaiting an FRA Movement Approval to destination for offloading of the product and then to home shop for re-qualification.    This incident did require a special switching move.    A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report was completed for this incident.    NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80    Cause codes: 414/209
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On August 26, 2012, at 0400 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Corbin Terminal, Corbin, KY, noticed a strong odor near GATX 45437, a loaded tank car of UN1299, Turpentine. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Resolute FP Canada Inc., was notified directly via their emergency contact phone number (807) 475-2400. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, responded and found the top operating bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) missing the operating rod. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, Vern Seymour (807) 475-2457. The vapor release was secured by covering the TOBOV assembly with a plastic bag.    On August 27, 2012, a CSXT hazardous material manager installed a wooden cylindrical plug into the void where the TOBOV operating rod was missing and replaced a deteriorated manway gasket. The exterior of the tank car was cleaned using a citrus degreasing agent and water solution to extract any residual material from the tank car.    GATX 45437 will be  transferred into UTLX 67449 and the shipper will request an FRA Movement Approval to home shop the car for repairs.    This incident did require a special move.    A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is required for this incident.    NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code: 551

column168: Carrier employee was unloading an IBC into consignee's tank when the fitting on the pump outlet broke.   The pump was located inside of an old tote modified to function as a containment bin so most of the product was confined to the bin.  Only a few ounces may not have been captured.  The carrier employee cleaned up the material lost due to the failure of the pump fitting.  The consginee was satisfied with the actions taken to clean up the spill.
column169: We have made all carrier drivers aware of this incident and have requested that they examine their pumps for any signs of cracking or other failure around the fittings.  We have also requested that the drivers and plant employees who perform this task relieve the stress caused by the weight of the heavy-duty hose on the pump outlet and fittings. This can be accomplished by use of bungee cords, an object such as a wood box or other method that will lessen the strain on the pump fitting.  We are also considering a modification of the pump/housing to incorporate some method of support for the hose and fitting.

column168: On August 9, 2012, a tanker containing UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid released approximately 250 gallons of product from the body of the tanker. The released material impacted an asphalt parking lot. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for initial response and remediation activities. The tanker was plugged and the remaining product was transferred into a replacement tanker. Soda ash was then applied to the impacted areas to neutralize the acid. Granular absorbents were then applied to the area and were worked in thoroughly. The waste was collected and containerized for disposal.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A release of approx 20 LOZ was reported as the shipment arrived to the consignee and was refused at approx. 10:30.  The IBC was not actively leaking but the container emitted an odor and liquid in the form of residue was present on the top of the container from the fusible cap. The IBC was deemed safe to transport and taken back to the carriers facility where the IBC was removed and isolated for inspection at approx. 11:30     An ER team was called at the request of the shipper to investigate the source of the problem and found the fusible cap was loose. The cap was tightened and the IBC was returned to the shipper. The shipper's later investigation revealed the gasket used to seal the fusible cap failed causing the minimal release.     The original delivery trailer the IBC was removed from was inspected and no residue was evident in the trailer and the IBC did not leak in transit back to the carrier's facility. The trailer was placed back in service and the other freight which was not impacted was offered for delivery. The carrier delivered four other shipments and made two pick ups on this trailer.     At 14:00 the carrier received a call from Sonic Electronics 20 minutes after the driver departed to advise they had employees affected by an odor emitting from our trailer and 1 was seen and released at a local hospital then immediately returned to duty. This was on August 8, 2012.      The information gathered by the carrier from the Pleasure Ridge Park Fire Department and Metro Sewer District indicated they found no evidence of a release or hazardous environment upon  arrival and cleared the scene after the carrier had supplied said agencies with the MSDS for the product that was previously contained in the trailer.    None of the other consignees that had contact with the trailer (two before the delivery to Sonic and three after) reported any affects resulting from their contact with the same trailer. As previously stated the container had been removed from the trailer and no residue was found 3 hours prior to arriving at Sonic.

DRIVER WAS EXITING I 30 EASTBOUND ONTO LOOP 12 WALTON WALKER BLVD TO GO SOUTHBOUND. YOU HAVE TO MAKE A RIGHT HAND TURN HEADED BACK WEST CROSSING BACK OVER LOOP 12 AND THEN MAKE A LEFT TURN/CURVE TO GO SOUTH. THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED COMING OUT OF THE LAST CURVE. DRIVER SAID THAT THERE WAS A BUMP IN THE ROAD AND HE OVER CORRECTED. THAT IS THE LAST THAT HE REMEMBERS. I HAVE ATTACHED A COPY OF THE ACCIDENT SITE ROADWAY. AS SOON AS WE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT WE CALLED TAS ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TO GO TO THE SCENE AND STOP OR PREVENT ANY SPILLIAGE. THEY PUMPED REMAINING FUEL FROM TRAILER INTO ONE OF OUR OTHER TRAILERS.
column169: HAVE A DRIVER MEETING TO DISCUSS ROLLOVER PREVENTION TO INCLUDE SPEED, ROAD CONDITIONS, OTHER TRAFFIC, FOCUSING ON THE ROAD AND KEEPING BOTH HANDS ON THE WHEEL. WILL HAVE DRIVERS REVIEW VIDEO ON ROLLOVER PREVENTION. REMIND DRIVERS WHAT CAN HAPPEN WHEN THESE THINGS ARE NOT PERFOMED PROPERLY.  DRIVER MEETING WAS HELD ON 8/22/12 CONSISTING OF ROLL OVER VIDEO AND DISCUSSION, SPEED CONTROL, ROAD CONDITIONS AND SAFETY.

column168: A 53 foot intermodal container SWRU 102583 was reported emanating a chemical odor at the BNSF intermodal facility. SWRU 102583 was moved and isolated at the facility's containment area awaiting response from the shipper representatives. In the morning of 8/11/2012, the shipper contract responders notified local BNSF personnel that the lading inside SWRU 102583 was smoldering and possibly on fire. Local F.D. agencies were notified and responded. Operations at the BNSF intermodal facility were ceased and all personnel were relocated. The F.D. hazardous material responders reported that the smoke/heat emanating from the intermodal container was created by a chemical reaction from some of the lading within SWRU 102583. After the smoke subsided and air quality returned to normal, the F.D. allowed operations at the intermodal facility to fully resume. Afterwards, the contract responders were able to remove the lading inside SWRU 102583 and initiate the clean-up process. Several pallets of consumer recreational pool care products were charred. These commercial swimming pool products were packaged 4 poly bottles per carton and these cartons were labeled as Oxidizers and some as Corrosives.   The Corrosive material was not declared on the shipping papers received by BNSF or by Swift Transport.  All recovered lading was earmarked for appropriate disposal.   Emptied SWRU 102583 was towed away from the BNSF intermodal facility.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED DUE TO IT BEING RUN OVER BY A TUG.  THERE WERE 6 PIGS IN THE PACKAGE AND ALL THE LIDS HAD COME OFF. THE SMASHED VIAL AND CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE RECOVERED AND WERE PLACED INTO A PLASTIC BAG AND SALVAGE DRUM. KEN HOLMAN OF THE MEM / FAA WAS CONTACTED AT 11:45 ON 08/13/2012 TO INFORM HIM OF THE INCIDENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING FURTHER FOLLOW-UP.

column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND BY UNLOADER ERIC ALLEN.  PACKAGE WAS RESPONDED TO BY JEFF SHULTS AND JEREMY ATTAWAY, FOLLOWING DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.  PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE AND USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  ALL CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A GREEN HAZMAT BAG.  THE PACKAGE HAD A 2.5 LITER GLASS BOTTLE OF SULFURIC ACID.  THE BOTTLE WAS PLACED IN A DOUBLE-FILL PACKING.  THE OUTER CONTAINER WAS NOT CRUSHED, BENT OR ABUSED FROM PHYSICAL OBSERVATION.  HOWEVER, THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTSIDE CONTAINER WAS COATED IN SULFURIC ACID SO AN OBSERVATION COULD NOT BE MADE ON THAT PART OF THE CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED WITH ORIENTATION ARROWS UP AND BLOCKED AND BRACED.  THE PACKAGE MAY HAVE BEEN DROPPED BUT THERE WERE NO INDICATIONS ON THE OUTER CONTAINER UNLESS DAMAGE ON THE BOTTOM WHERE AN OBSERVATION COULD NOT BE MADE.
column169: USE BETTER PACKING FOR GLASS BOTTLES THAT CAN WITHSTAND TRANSPORT OR BEING ACCIDENTLY DROPPED.

column168: At 00:33 PDT hours, San Joaquin Valley Railroad (SJVR) trainmaster Nick Mojarro noticed a release near the Buttonwillow subdivision in Bakersfield California from tank car #RCRX2482. Hydrochloric acid (UN 1789) was dripping off the tank car. There were no homes or businesses in the area, the tank car was sitting on level ground on track #1918 on the Wible Orchard siding, and the only surface water was approximately a half mile away. Notifications made included: RailAmerica Environmental Director Rick Norris (00:52 PDT), Bakersfield Fire Department (01:02 PDT), California State Warning Center (01:11 PDT, case #12-4679), NRC (01:20 PDT, case #1020580), Kern County CUPA (01:28 PDT). At 12:30 PDT Conestoga-Rovers & Associates (CRA) staff arrived at the scene to assist. SJVR staff had already applied soda ash to the surface to neutralize the acid and washed down the tank car. The vent valve had been tightened and secured and the tank car returned to service. CRA staff assessed the extent of moisture in soil from the acid/rinse water and assisted SJVR staff in mixing in additional soda ash as needed to neutralize any remaining acid. There are no surface or ground water resources at risk at this location. Before leaving the site, CRA staff visually determined that the acid at the surface had been neutralized and that there was no remaining contact risk for pedestrian trespassers. Site actions were complete by 14:15 PDT. CRA personnel contacted Craig Perkins with the Bakersfield Fire Department and Gabe Rubio with the Kern County Environmental Health Department to confirm that the incident had been reported and that no additional filings were necessary.
column169: SJVR continues to inspect all railcars for potential spills/leaks and will continue to do so. No additional recommendations are provided at this time.

column168: After the local F.D. released intermodal container SWRU 102583 that was previously smoldering from a chemical reaction at the BNSF intermodal facility, shipper contract responders were allowed to remove the lading inside SWRU 102583 and initiate the clean-up process. Some pallets of consumer recreational pool care products were charred. These commercial swimming pool products were packaged 4 poly bottles per carton and these cartons were labeled as Oxidizers and some as Corrosives. The Corrosive material was not declared on the shipping papers received by BNSF or by Swift Transport.  Several pallets of Corrosive labeled cartons were removed from SWRU 102583. Some of the lading that remained within SWRU 102583 was damaged and unrecognizable. This damaged lading was removed from the container and held for appropriate disposal. All other recovered lading was earmarked for appropriate disposal. Emptied SWRU 102583 was towed away from the BNSF intermodal facility.

column168: At approximately 16:30 on August 15,2012, Dock man John Sanger was off loading a trailer that was against the dock at ABF-Chester, Pa (185), terminal. There was a small crate on the back of the unit he was off loading. As John proceeded to off load this crate his forks extended though the crate and punctured one of the drums ahead of the crate causing the spill. The spill was contained on dock and the spill was handled in house.
column169: Sat down with Mr. John Sanger (dock man), and discussed the importance of proceeding with caution upon entering trailers with drums. Emphazing the importance of knowing what freight lay ahead of shipments that you are currently off loading, and knowing how far your forks are into the skid that you are presently handling as not to cause damage to shipments in front. All other personel were briefed of this incident as to bring awareness of the dangers of not properly proceeding into skids( being off loaded with a forklift), without being fully aware of what shipments lie ahead. As a general rule, the route driver will inform all dock men of any hazardous material that was picked up on his route during that day as an added precaution to make that dock man aware of the importance of off loading shipments with caution to prevent future recurrence of what happened.

column168: ON 08/08/12 AT APPROXIMATELY 0830 HOURS, THE AIRGAS TRACTOR TRAILER (TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON K-61) IMPACTED A CONSTRUCTION VEHICLE OPERATING AS AN ADVANCE WARNING VEHICLE FOR MACHINERY THAT WAS SANDBLASTING THE OUTSIDE FOG LINE FROM THE ROADWAY. THE FRONT RIGHT PORTION OF THE AIRGAS VEHICLE STRUCK THE BACK LEFT SIDE OF THE CONSTRUCTION VEHICLE.    THE COLLISION WAS CAUSED BY THE AIRGAS DRIVER BENDING DOWN TO PICK UP A BOTTLE OF WATER FROM THE FLOOR BOARD OF THE AIRGAS VEHICLE. WHEN THE AIRGAS DRIVER LOOKED UP HE SWERVED AND IMPACTED THE CONSTRUCTION VEHICLE WHILE SWERVING TO THE LEFT WHERE HE CONTINUED ACROSS THE LEFT LANE AND ACROSS THE MEDIAN. THE AIRGAS VEHICLE WAS BROUGHT TO REST ON THE INSIDE SHOULDER OF THE NB K-61.    AS THE AIRGAS VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING THROUGH THE MEDIAN A 95 LB PROPANE TANK (GOUGED DURING THE COLLISION WITH THE CONSTRUCTION VEHICLE SIGN) RELEASED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. DUE TO THE NATURE OF PROPANE BEING EXPELLED IN AN UNCONTROLLED AND VIOLENT FASHION, THE GAS CAUGHT FIRE. THE FIRE LASTED NO LONGER THAN 20 SECONDS AND WAS EXTINGUISHED BY THE AIRGAS DRIVER. MCPHERSON, KS FIREFIGHTERS REMOVED THE TANK FROM THE VEHICLE AND PLACED IT INTO THE EAST DITCH. NO FURTHER DAMAGE WAS MADE TO OTHER CYLINDERS ON THE LOAD.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL TRAINING, PACKAGING, OR OPERATING PROCEDURES CAN PREVENT THIS TYPE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE FROM RECURRING. THIS WAS A CASE OF A DRIVER REMOVING HIS ATTENTION FROM THE ROAD.

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD MADE THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE UNLOADING HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING POINT AND HAD JUST BEGAN TO PUMP OFF THE TANKER OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WHEN THE 2" CPVC THREADED CAMLOCK FITTING IN THE CUSTOMER'S PIPELINE THAT OUR HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO, CRACKED AND BROKE. THE CUSTOMER'S REPRESENTATIVE WAS STANDING NEXT TO THE UNLOADING CONNECTION WHEN HE SAW THE CRACK DEVELOP AND THE PRODUCT BEGINNING TO LEAK AND GIVEN THAT OUR DRIVER WAS STANDING AT THE REAR OF THE TANKER NEXT TO THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TANKER, HE WAS ABLE TO IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS RESULTING IN A MINIMAL LOSS OF PRODUCT.    IT IS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND THIS WAS CONTAINED IN THE CUSTOMER'S DRAIN SYSTEM THAT FEEDS THEIR CONTAINMENT TANK.
column169: THE CUSTOMER'S REPRESENTATIVE HAS STATED THAT THIS PARTICULAR THREADED CAMLOCK FITTING HAD BEEN REPLACED APPROXIMATELY ONE MONTH AGO AND THAT THERE IS NO CLEAR AND DEFINABLE EXPLANATION AS TO WHY THIS FAILED. THE MATERIAL OF CONSTRUCTION IS COMPATIBLE WITH THE PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED AND THE FITTING WAS REPLACED BY THE CUSTOMER.

column168: CTMV transporting fuel oil was involved in an accident which resulted in the release of product from impact damage points on the vessel.  The accident location consisted of several sharp curves in rapid session.  The posted speed limit prior to entering the first curve is 55 MPH.  The accident scene consisted of unfinished roadway markings and signage due to the recently performed roadway maintenance activity including resurfacing the roadway itself.    This accident is the result of several factors including time of day (02:20), missing safety warning signage and roadway markings identifying designated lanes.  When our driver entered the curve he was unable to identify critical safety references such as lane designations which would have indicated the severity of the curve.  Driver negotiated two of the three curves and went off the paved surface in the third curve and into the ditch on the side of the roadway.  The vehicle overturned and made impact with a fence.  Driver was injured and vehicle was totaled.
column169: Actions required to prevent accidents such as this one should include both roadway compliance with federal safety markings and signage requirements and increased driver training.  The training will deal with increased dangers associated with later night driving, increased awareness of the importance of road signage and markings along with review of the forces in motion which affect vehicle stability and control resulting from sharp curves and turns involving loaded CTMVs.    It is our position that this accident could have been prevented if the required signage and roadway safety markings were in place.  They have since been installed by the state of Texas. This is an excellent example of the forces in play when cargo tank loads are forced to be redirected before they have had a chance to settle down.  Studies and field tests have shown that two or more curves in close proximity to each other will multiply the forces in motion and decrease stability control of the vehicle.      An additional recommendation was made for this portion of the roadway to have a cautionary 35 MPH speed limit for commercial motor vehicles.

column168: A SHIPMENT OF EIGHT (8) WL-23761 GAMMA DETECTORS CONTAINING UN1956, COMPRESSED GAS, N.O.S. (NITROGEN, HELIUM, CARBON DIOXIDE) WITH A LIMITED QUANTITY OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL (CARBON 14) WAS PLACED INTO TRANSPORTATION AS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE GAMMA DETECTORS WERE PACKAGED FOR SHIPMENT. THE SHIPYAR DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPPING DIRECTIVE HAD DISCREPANCIES CONCERNING THE QUANTITY OF DETECTORS (8) FOR SHIPMENT AND THE SHIPMENT ADDRESS. VERBAL DIRECTION WAS GIVEN NOT TO SHIP THE MATERIAL. PRIOR TO RESOLUTION OF THESE DESCREPANCIES, THE MATERIAL WAS ERRONEOUSLY MOVED TO THE SHIPPING AREA AND PLACED INTO TRANSPORTATION AS GENERAL FREIGHT MATERIAL. DOT REQUIREMENT (I.E., SHIPPING PAPERS, PACKAGE MARKING AND LABELING) WERE NOT PROPERLY COMMUNICATED.  THE GAMMA DETECTORS ARE DESIGNED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 173.310, HOWEVER, THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT DESIGNED OR BUILT IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 173.310(C).  ACTIONS TAKEN AT TIME OF DISCOVERY: SHIPYARD CONTACTED CARRIER TO RETURN TO SHIPMENT TO NORFOLK NAVAL SHIPYARD. NO RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS FOUND DURING UNLOADING SUBSEQUENT TO TRANSPORTATION.
column169: The eight (8) WL-23761 gamma detectors have been marked to identify the hazardous content and moved to a secure location. The shipyard procedural instruction for storage and shipping of Radiological Affairs Support Program radiation detectors will be revised to incorporate identification of hazardous content and to require storage in a secure location. Appropriate personnel will be trained on the procedural changes and the 49 CFR 173.310 shipment requirements for radiation detectors. Packaging and procedural guidance has been developed by Mirion Technologies 1ST Corporation in accordance with 49 CFR 173.310 for future shipments of gamma detectors. These instructions will be implemented in local shipyard operating procedures and training provided to appropriate personnel.

column168: Shipment was loaded on 8/17/2012 at 12:49 PM at Williams Field Services, Ignacio Plant for Ortega's Propane in Algodones, NM.  On Hightway 550, near mile marker 29, the driver heard a loud noise and noticed that the commerical motor vehicle immediately began losing air. After safely negotiating the commerical motor vehicle to a stop, the driver exited the vehicle and found one of the fuel tanks to be on fire. The driver attempted to extinguish the fire with a fire extinguisher.  The fuel line between the two fuel tanks was severed and the fire could not be extinguished.  The heat from the fire caused the pressure of the product in the MC 331 cargo tank motor vehicle to rise.  Vapor was released from the pressure relief device at the front of the MC 331 cargo tank motor vehicle. Once the burning commerical motor vehicle was extinguished, the product remaining in the MC 331 cargo tank motor vehicle was transferred to another cargo tank motor vehicle and delivered to Algodones, NM.

column168: Tank car GBRX 700251 entrained in an inbound BNSF train entering the railyard was reported with a fresh product stain on its side shell. A BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responder was notified and inspected GBRX 700251. The responder relieved internal pressure within GBRX 700251 and reported the leak source was at the liquid valve's closure plug which was not tool tight. The liquid valve's operating handle was in the closed position. The liquid valve's plug was removed; plug threads cleaned and new thread sealant applied. The plug was reinserted and properly tool tightened which ended any further product release. Afterwards, GBRX 700251 was set-out from its inbound train and isolated in the railyard for exterior cleaning. No further leakage was observed prior to and after GBRX 700251 was power-washed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

At approximately 1400 hours on 8/22/12 the PTRA was notified of a leaking tank car, TEAX 3018, located on track 100 in the Storage Yard by TXDOT HM Inspector Horton. PTRA notified the shipper, Intercontinental Terminals Company, and M&M Protection to respond to the location to determine the cause and stop the leak. Upon arrival it was discovered that there was a vapor leak between the protective housing and the liquid line valve flange.  ITC attempted to tighten the flange bolts to stop the leak. M&M took gas readings after the initial attempt and did not show any leak present. The following morning, 8/23/12, the car was inspected again and the vapor leak was present in the same location. ITC made another unsuccessful attempt to stop the leak. At that time they sealed the flange bolt area with silicon sealant and the car was set out awaiting an FRA Movment Approval to return the car to ITC for off loading and repairs. The root cause has not been determined. At this time, 9/19/12, we believe it could be a bad gasket or defective housing nozzle.
column169: ITC will conduct a thorough investigation of the car once it is returned to the plant.

column168: Our vehicle was leaving our facility crossing Highway 54 in a construction area. There were cars stopped on the roadway waiting for a pilot car. Our Chevrolet truck was pulling a 1000 gallon nurse tank of anhydrous ammonia to a farmers field. The truck was hit broadside on the passenger side by an oncoming construction semi tractor and belly dump rock trailer. The impact knocked the truck off the road and ripped the tongue of the wagon in 2. The wagon stayed on the highway and was impacted by the front corner of the rock trailer in the head of the nurse tank. The impact punctured the tank leaving a 8 inch gash about an inch wide. The nurse tank spun around and tipped over after impact and released most of its contents for about 5 minutes until it froze over. We then picked it up, put it on a flatbed and hauled it to a remote farm field to empty the rest of the contents. That product was contained with water from fire trucks. That product was picked up and land applied. The product released on the roadway immediately following the collision vapored off into the atmosphere, there was no environmental contamination. Our driver was stuck in the cloud of ammonia for a period of time and suffered inhalation exposure. He was stuck in the truck because the seatbelt was so tight around him it was hard to get off.
column169: In this incident the release was a result of a vehicle accident. The semi that hit us was not following the pilot car at the time of the collision. The pilot car was behind it.

column168: Driver departed the terminal at 11:33 in Butler, IN, with a full tanker.  At 13:43, the driver took a 5 minute break at rest area 3.76 miles south of Fowlerton, IN.  No vapor or leaks were detected at this time.  About 15:00, the driver noticed vaport coming from the rear of the trailer.  The driver immediately exited I-65 South at exit 103.  Vehicle was stopped and off the road as far as possible by 15:13.  Driver opened cabinet at the rear of the trailer and allowed the vapor to dissipate for several minutes before attempting to locate the leak.  As the vapor dissipated, the driver began tightening all valves on the trailer cabinet.  The top fill valve was discovered to have come loose in transport.  Driver tightened the top fill valve and the leak immediately stopped.  By 15:30, the leak was secured and local police arrived at the scene.  Driver was underway at 16:07 to his delivery destination.

column25: M-Bar-D Railcar Tech Inc. by Missouri Valley Petroleum Inc./J5 Transport
column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector in the railyard observed tank car NTRX 29035 dripping residue product from its bottom outlet valve's (BOV) closure cap (BOC). The FRA Inspector reported the bottom operated BOV's operating handle was in the closed position, but it was not pinned by the securing pin. No shipper seals were observed at the BOV. Also, all six manway securement bolts were hanging down (not applied). A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified of NTRX 29035's leaking condition. The BNSF responder reported the BOC was tool tightened approximately 1 1/2 turns which ended any further product drips from around the BOC. The BOV operating handle was then pinned with the securing pin in its closed position. All manway securement bolts were properly positioned and tool tightened.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: SRIX 83106 was reported to be leaking only when moving, by yard personnel.  A contractor was notified and responded to the scene along with the Louisianna State Police.  The contractor inspected the car and found a missing manway gasket.  A new manway gasket was installed and the manway properly secured.  A second small leak was also noticed on the bottom outlet valve at the cap.  The threads and cap were wet and appeared to be leaking past the threads.  The cap was turned approximately 1/2 turn until tight and the leak continued.  The car was monitored throughout the night.  The shipper recieved verbal FRA approval to move the car into their yard under 174.50 and off load the car there.  Their yard was at the end of the Riverfront yard.  The car was moved and spotted at 1430 hours on 8/20/12 and the offloading began by their personnel.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: UPRR Manager of Terminal Operations reported an unknown amount of product released from the top of tank car GATX 49431 within the Nampa Rail yard at Nampa Idaho.  Leon Hendrickson, UPRR Manager of Hazardous Materials was notified and Pacific West, Emergency Response Contractor responded.  After a inspection of the car it was discovered approximately 3 to 5 gallons of product had been released to the top and sides of the car.  The release was from a ruptured frangible disk.  A new disk was installed of like kind.  The car was isolated where it was decontaminated.   The car was properly secured, re-inspected and released to destination.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: A release was observed coming from container UMXU 933601 located in the Union Pacific Global 1 Rail Yard. The release involved Amines Liquid, Corrosive N.O.S. and was a result of a load shift due to inadequate blocking and bracing by the shipper. As a result a total of 1 gallon of material was released to the pavement.     Floor blocking should have been utilized to prevent lateral movement of totes during rail transportation. The inadequate B+B caused the front right nose tote to shift into the front left nose tote resulting in the crushing of the tote and to subsequently release the HZ material.
column169: Use floor blocking to prevent movement of totes. Container was reworked with the utilization of a front bulkhead. All totes were floor blocked with 2 x 6 material.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-LIMITED QUANTITY OF MATERIAL
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Sequence of Events:  A Radioactive Material, Excepted Package limited Quantity of Material package (10 gallon drum) containing a torque wrench testing bench and associated cable was shipped from Brunswick Nuclear Plant (BNP) via UPS to Duke Energy EnRad laboratories on 8/20/2012. The package was delivered by UPS along with several other packages on 8/21/12 at 10:45.  Warehouse personnel did a quick inspection and placed the package in the EnRad radioactive material storage area.    Upon inspection by EnRad Radiation Protection personnel, it was discovered that the package had been breached in 2 locations (see attached photographs). The breach consisted of a slit approximately 2 inches in length in the upper section of the drum and a smaller puncture in the lower section of the drum.  The breaches were caused by the equipment inside the drum puncturing the wall of the drum. Additionally, it was noted that the package has significant damage overall.    Radiation and contamination surveys were immediately conducted on the external surfaces of the package. No external package removable contamination was detected.  The package was opened and additional contamination surveys were conducted inside the package. No removable contamination was detected on the inside of the drum or on the equipment inside the package.    BNP Management, EnRad Management, and Duke Energy Fleet Services Management were notified of the incident.  It was determined that the event was a DOT Hazardous Material incident requiring notification of the DOT. Duke Energy EnRad Laboratories accepted the responsibility for reporting the incident, even though the breach occurred during transport, since they had received the package. The DOT National Response Center was notified of the incident on 8/21/12 at 19:30. Additionally, EnRad made courtesy calls to the NC State Radioactive Materials Branch after hour number and to Mecklenburg County Emergency Management.  BNP notified their resident NRC inspector and American Nuclear Insurance of the event.  Description of Package:  The packaging was a certified DOT Type A Package (UN/1A/X/201S/04) certified for 2651bs of material. The drum lid was torque as required.  The torque wrench bench was made of steel and had rounded corners but the edges were relatively sharp metal.  It weighed approximately 95 pounds.  The torque wrench bench was placed in the drum at an angle with a sharp edge resting on the floor and the sharp edges of the top of the bench leaning on the upper walls of the drum.  The bottom edge of the bench on the floor of the drum was padded with layers of cloth. The upper section of the bench was wrapped in bubble wrap.  Condition of Package at Destination (see attached photographs):  The bottom rim of the drum was crumpled from the outside in a manner that indicated that the drum had a significant impact when the drum was at an angle (e.g.; potentially dropped on bottom rim when drum was at an angle).  The floor of the drum was di
column169: 1.   The shipper (BNP) has ceased all shipments of radioactive materials via common carrier and will utilize the services of a contracted courier service to transport excepted packages of radioactive material and equipment this will provide more accountability and oversight for the quality of routine hazardous materials transportation.  2.   Reviewed the event and provided additional training and guidance with BNP receiving warehouse facility personnel on the need to do a detailed inspection of packages (both radioactive and non-radioactive) prior to releasing the driver of the carrier delivering the packages. Early identification of damaged packages will help in the investigation and the accountability for the damage.  3.   Reviewed the event and provided additional training and guidance with BNP Radwaste Shipping group personnel on the need to consider unexpected transport conditions when shoring and packaging items that may encounter conditions outside of the expected conditions of transport, i.e. normal jostling, bumps and moving container from one truck to another during the contracted transport period (normal conditions of transport).  4.   BNP is reviewing for purchase, improved package options for transporting material that can be considered a higher risk during normal transportation circumstances, such as heavy, sharp, breakable, items and equipment.

column168: FRED W. WAS WORKING AT THE PICK AT S 1-D7.TO DO HIS JOB, THERE WAS A BELT STOP IN PLACE IN FRONT OF HIM. THERE WERE ONLY A FEW PACKAGES ON THE BELT AS THE SORT HAD JUST BEGUN. FRED STARTED TO PICK A BOX AT THE STOP BAR, WHEN HE NOTICED A CHEMICAL SMELL. HE LOOKED MORE CLOSELY AT THE BOX AND REALIZED THAT IT WAS BOTH ON ITS SIDE AND LEAKING. HE TURNED OFF THE BELT, CLIMBED DOWN, AND FOUND HIS PT SUP. WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE PICK LOCATION, I FOUND THAT THE LEAK HAD CAUSED A HUGE PUDDLE ON THE BELT. FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, I APPLIED LARGE AMOUNTS OF SODIUM BICARBONATE TO THE PUDDLE UNTIL I GOT A NEUTRAL PH READING. ALL OF THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS BROUGHT TO OUR RESPONDER PIT WHERE IT WAS PROCESSED.
