column168: At the Charlotte TRANSFLO-WEST (Food Grade) terminal, the employee was setting up for his first ethanol transload for the day. This transfer of ethanol from railcar to truck is conducted with a electric mobile pump. On the mobile pump there is a filter that must be inspected before the pump is used. As part of his pre-inspection checklist, the employee opened the filter housing to visually inspect the filter but did not tighten the locking bolt on the filter housing after inspection. He continued the setup of the transfer by connecting the grounding cables, vapor recovery lines, product hose to the railcar, and plugging up the electric pump. From underneath the railcar he then opened up the product valve allowing ethanol to flow to the pump. After coming out from under the car he noticed ethanol oozing out from the partially cracked open filter lid on the pump. He moved in the closer to inspect the oozing product and when he touched the filter lid, it popped off from the pressure that had built up in the filter and ethanol began to flow from the pump filter. It took approximately 7 seconds for the employee to get back to the railcar to shut off the product valve and stop the flow of ethanol. He radioed for a spill response and several employees came to assist with applying oil absorbents and sand on the impacted area. Approximately 20 gallons of denatured ethanol was released onto the asphalt surface. No drains, soil, or water were impacted from the release. The contaminated oil dry and sand was swept up and placed into appropriate containers for scheduled pick up and appropriate removal. At 06:14 the Terminal Manager called the Area Ops Director and he in turn contacted KMMS EHS and all other appropriate parties (TRANSFLO). The NRC was contacted at 7:05 to report the release since the Reportable Quantity was exceeded.
column169: Direct/Intermediate Causes  Failure to follow procedure/Policy/Practice  •Employee failed to fully complete the inspection of his equipment utilizing the daily equipment checklist  •Employee failed to follow pre-transfer procedures in Procedure # 3025- Transferring Ethanol Via Metered Pump   •Employee failed to refer to form 1642 B indicating that the equipment inspection is completed  •Employee failed to recognize the risk in not completing one task before moving to the next  •Before opening the railcar the employee failed to stop and make a mental note that all connections were in tack     Basic / Root Causes:   •Extreme judgment / decision demands - Employee was focused on setting up the railcars for the day   •Lack of situational awareness- Although the employee did not feel the need to stop he failed to recognize that before he opened the railcar there is a need to retrace his steps to ensure that all openings are secure.  •Improper attempt to save time or effort - Thinking that he would save some time he stopped the task of inspecting the filter and moved directly to hooking up the railcar fittings    Corrective Actions Taken:  •Review transloading procedure # 3025 (Transferring Ethanol Via Metered Pump) to ensure that controls that are incorporated into policies and procedures are utilized.     •Retrain all employees on transload procedure # 3025 and use form 1642B to ensure that critical tasks are performed.

column58: Liquid Line; Loading or Unloading Lines
column168: A car ahead of our unit lost control and flipped upside down across both East bound lanes of Interstate 10.  Our driver stopped in the left lane of the interstate and another commercial motor vehicle ran into the rear of our trailer shearing the liquid line and the vapor line off of our trailer.  The spray bar line was bent upward in a 45 degree angle which tore the bottom of the pipe allowing vapor to seep out.       Louisiana State Police, Hazardous Materials Division incident commander on the scene made the decision to "Vent and Burn" the product off of our cargo tank.  Shaped charges were placed on the top and bottom of our trailer, then were detonated.  As the product was escaping from our tank, it was set on fire by the use of a flare and allowed to burn until our cargo tank was empty.
column169: We do not believe our employee could have done anything to prevent this accident.  We have no suggestions to help prevent recurrence of incidents such as this.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. arrived at Clean Harbors Buttonwillow, LLC transporting a hazardous waste shipment comprised of arsenic contaminated debris.  The shipment in question that offered for transportation by Phillips Lumileds Lighting Company located in San Jose, CA.  Upon arrival samples of the waste material were taken and tested in compliance with the facility’s waste analysis plan.  All waste verification test results met the waste acceptance parameters and was approved for unloading at the appropriate unloading bay.   Upon arrival at the off-loading bay, the vehicle operator opened the container and proceeded to unload the roll-off container.  Approximately 5 – 10 percent of the material was off-loaded when a small fire was observed on the outside of one of the boxes that had been unloaded and it involved an area approximately 10 inches by 10 inches.  Facility personnel immediately extinguished the fire with a hand held extinguisher.  Immediately after extinguishing the fire, facility personnel contacted the onsite emergency coordinator who shut down operations in this one specific bay in order to investigate the incident.  In addition, the roll-off container was moved to a secure location to safeguard personnel and property should another fire breakout.    An investigation was initiated that included member of Clean Harbors and Phillips Illumined Lighting.  Upon consultation with the offeror, it is was determined that a either a small portion of the debris may have inadvertently come into contact with white phosphorous or a small amount of white phosphorous may have been shipped in the roll-off.    It was then decided to sort the remaining material and identify any additional materials that may have been contaminated with this material.  During the sorting process, Clean Harbor’s personnel removed and containerized 1 30 gallon container of debris that was suspected to contain a small percentage of white phosphorous.  This material was rejected back to the offeror for proper disposal.  The remaining load was received and processed at the facility without incident.
column169: At the time the material was offered for transportation, the driver inspected the shipment and there were no indications that a problem existed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, Clean Harbors suspended the acceptance of this waste stream until the offeror confirmed that they took all appropriate steps to insure cross contamination of waste streams did not occur that could result in a repeat occurrence.

column168: PUMPING CAUSTIC INTO CUSTOMERS TANK.  DRIVER CHECKED TANK AND HOSE. DRIVER CHECKED PRESSURE AND ALL WAS OK. DRIVER RECHECKED PRESSURE 5 MINS LATER AND FOUND IT HAD GONE UP TO 40 PSI,  DRIVER CHECKED INTERNAL HYDRAULIC VALVE AND FOUND IT DOWN (CLOSED)  DRIVER RELEASED PRESSURE AND CAUSTIC SPILLED FROM THE HOSE.  DRIVER CONTAINED WITH A 5 GALLON BUCKET.  DRIVER REPORTED THE PRESSURE STARTED TO DROP AND WHILE GOING TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO THE VALVE AREA DRIVER TIPPED THE BUCKET SPILLING ABOUT 4 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE 50 % SOLUTION.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED THE FICILITIES ENGINEER TO REPORT THE SPILL AND ASK FOR ASSISTANCE.  THE ENGINEER CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND BOTH THE FACILITY AND UNIVAR CALLED THE DEP.  UNIVAR CALLED CYN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN THE SPILL.  DRIVER RECHECKED ALL EQUIPMENT AND PUMPED OFF THE REST OF THE LOAD.

column168: INCIDENT SUMMARY Job #   1130-01854  Client:  Gary Marsh I TREC Environmental    Location: I-10 west bound on ramp MM 44    By: Edward Schultz    Thursday 8-16-12    11:00   USES received a call from Earl Etheridge with MDEQ concerning an 18 wheeler with a leaking drum of Polyphosphoric Acid 110%.    12:30  USES is on site and walking through the scene with MDEQ and the firemen that are on site.    12:45  USES has talked with Gary Marsh concerning the incident and has been notified that they will be working for TREC Environmental.    13:00  USES has ordered three roll off boxes and a 12000lb extended reach fork lift to unload the trailer so that is can be de-contaminated.  The trailer has been deemed not road worthy by the Mississippi Highway Patrol Motor Carrier division.    13:15   USES is awaiting the arrival of the equipment that has been ordered and the roll offboxes to load the drums in.    17:30  The extended reach fork lift is on sight.  USES has also ordered a light plant for when the sun goes down.    17:45  The roll off boxes have started to show up and USES is helping place the boxes in the proper location for easy loading.    18:00  USES has begun the unloading of the good and damaged drums placing them back on the pallets that are still in good shape in the trailer.    20:30   USES is still working on the unloading of the trailer.  The first roll off is loaded and headed to the Biloxi office for safe storage.    21:15   USES has begun to load the second roll off.    22:30   USES has finished loading the second roll off and has put all of the broken pallets and other miscellaneous trash in the third roll off box.    23:30   USES is back at the Biloxi office and off the clock with the exception of Paul Newton who is headed back to Mobile. column168: On 08/02/2012, a passenger & his wife were waiting in the boarding area of Gate A34 for assistance to board their flight to LIT when Vaughn Hamby, a Frontier customer service agent, noticed the passenger assembling a personal oxygen system.  The agent proceeded to ask the passenger for paperwork for his personal oxygen concentrator (POC), as well as verifying his machine. It was then that the agent realized it was not a POC but a small tank of oxygen. The agent called for assistance from a supervisor. Supervisor Giavanni Carballo spoke with the passenger about the oxygen bottles. The passenger was elderly and stated that he was unaware of Frontier's policies concerning POCs or oxygen bottles, which was why he did not declare them. He stated that he had brought the bottles from LAX (Flight 404, Aircraft N905FR, LAX-DEN) but had not used them in flight. He stated that they were for backup and used only on an as-needed basis. After explaining Frontier policy with an emphasis on safety, Mr. Carballo gave a copy of Frontier's oxygen policy to the passenger, along with a blank copy of our POC doctor authorization form for future reference. He then voluntarily give up the bottle of oxygen he had out, stating he would be fine in the air without it. He did, however, attempt to hide a second bottle which he did not bother to mention. He insisted that the second bottle was empty, but subsequent inspection found that it was not. He then surrendered the second bottle after being told he could not board the aircraft with the oxygen bottle.

column168: Driver reported for duty at 0702 the morning of the accident. From 0702 to 0900 driver performed normal duties including loading his truck. Driver was in transit from 0900 until the time of the crash or 0925. Operator stated that "a bee flew into the driver compartment striking him on the face. He then "swatted the bee with both hands loosing control the truck". Driver heading South on Rt 15 Tioga County. Route 15 is in great condition with little traffic. There were no pot holes, sharp corners, oil slicks or any other road or weather issues noted during the time of the accident.  Truck rolled at least one compplete revolution before resting on the driver side and sliding 136 feet to rest. According to the driver the truck engine compartment and cab were on fire prior to resting. Driver unbuckled seatbelt and kicked out the front windshield to escape cab. Driver was unhurt. Fire then spread to tank section of the truck igniting the first compartment.  Firefighters arrived on scene and immediatly put water and foam on the burning truck. The then constructed a dam to control the release of fuel and water. The truck continued to burn for approx. 3 hours.
column169: A full investigation was conducted post accident with input from Pennsylvania State Police. PA. Department of Environmental Protection and Contracted HAZMAT group.  Internal policies and provedures are being modified to prevent this type of accident from occuring again. Specifically, training and experience factors will be changed to meet the challanges we face today.

column168: HERE IS THE DESCRIPTION OF THE INCIDENT FROM RALEIGH MIDNIGHT HUB MANAGER - RYAN.  AROUND 1AM, MY DURNC LOADER, JARREL, PICKED UP A PACKAGE OFF THE SLIDE AND NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING A BLUE LIQUID.  HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED PACKAGE ON CATWALK AND AS HE WAS GOING DOWN THE STEPS TO NOTIFY HIS SUPERVISOR, HE HEARD A POP.  WHEN JOHN ARRIVED ON BAY 105, HE SAW PACKAGE SWELL LIKE A BALLOON AND THEN HE STARTED TO SEE BLUE FLAMES.  JOHN FUMBLED WITH HIS RADIO AND CALLED ME ON THE RADIO SAYING HE HAD A FIRE ON BAY 105.  HE INSTRUCTED HIS EMPLOYEES TO MOVE FROM THE AREA TO SECURE IT AND THEN GRABBED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND DOUSED THE PACKAGE. JARREL ALSO GRABBED ANOTHER FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO HELP.  WHEN I ARRIVED, APPROXIMATELY 3 MINUTES AFTER JOHN CALLED ON THE RADIO, HE HAD THE FIRE PUT OUT WITH THE EXCEPTION OF A FEW EMBERS WHICH I USED THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO PUT OUT.  NO EMPLOYEES WERE INJURED.  WE EVACUATED BOTH D3 AND BROWN BELT TO LET THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER SMOKE DIMINISH.      SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT--  THIS REPORT SUPPLEMENTS AN INITIAL REPORT FILED FOR THE SAME DATE, LOCATION AND PACKAGE TRACKING NUMBER. ADDITIONAL INFORMATION OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER IDENTIFIED THE PRESENCE OF AN INNER CONTAINER OF UN1903 IN THE PACKAGE, IN ADDITION TO UN2880. IT IS POSSIBLE THE COMBINATION OF THESE TWO MATERIALS MAY HAVE CAUSED OR CONTRIBUTED TO THE FIRE INVOLVING THIS PACKAGE.
column169: MAKE SURE THAT THE SHIPPERS KNOW THE CONSEQUENCES OF SHIPPING UNDECLARED HAZMATS.

column168: An Elkhorn company driver was transporting a load (8400 gallons) of butane from the Roystone Plant to Bath, NY.  The driver was driving east on HWY (RT.) 66 and was attempting to make a left turn at the intersection of HWY (RT.) 66. While making the turn the left side of the trailer came off the ground, ultimately tipping the truck and trailer onto their right side.  Assessment of Root Cause: The driver needed to make a wider than normal turn due to a vehicle that was "nosed out" into the intersection.  This wide turn put the driver and transport onto a pitched section of the road surface.  While the drivers speed would not have been excessive for a "normal" turn, the combination of the wide turn, sloped (pitched) road and speed caused the liquid load to shift and put the whole transport unit off balance.  Assessment of Contributing Cause(s): Because of the wider than normal turn, the left side of the trailer raised the fenders and the hydraulic lines of the trailer caught on the frame rails of the truck, preventing the two from pivoting.  The weight of the trailer then pushed the truck over to the road curb where it was "tripped" and went over onto its right side.  Mitigating Circumstances: The rigid construction of the tank trailer allowed it to withstand the impact without rupturing or leaking. (NO Release)
column169: 1) Investigate if distance between trailer and hitch point can be extended to allow pivoting when making wider turns.                                                                   2) Assign driver refresher training to transport driver involved in incident.           3) Investigate the need to change travel times for transport trucks to daylight hours to avoid the hazards that come with nighttime driving and to increase sight conditions.  4) Discuss this incident and findings with all Elkhorn transport drivers.

column168: • Received a phone call at approximately 1:30PM,from  a motorist by the name of Jim Carter, who was behind Northwest Unit 2303 driven by Daniel Martin. The unit were Northbound on 15,north of Seattle,WA  • Mr Carter advised that a pop up valve or cap had come off the trailer, and a release of the product, which was Boral, landed on his service truck. Mr Carter was also concerned for his own well being, but  was unsure if any of the product had come in the open window of his truck, and was on his person. Mr Carter wanted to know what he should expect if he did come into contact with the product, and what he should do. I asked Mr Carter if he felt a burning sensation, or had any skin irritations,and he advised that he did not, but did say that he felt a tingling sensation in his arms and legs, that he believed may have been nerves due to the incident. I advised Mr Carter that if he was at all concerned with his well being, that he should seek immediate medical attention.  • After talking to Mr Carter, I asked Frank Scanlan, Operations Supervisor for NWTl, if he was aware of the incident. Frank told me that he was, and that he received a call from Mr Carter moments before I did, advising that something had blown off the trailer, causing a release of product. Mr Carter did not say anything to Frank about a possible Injury,so due to the fact the cell reception was poor, Frank's main  concern  was to get off the phone with Mr Carter,and contact the driver,In order tostop the truck, and have the driver inspect the unit for any leaks.  • Contacted Daniel Martin to try and get more information as to what happened, and develop an action plan. Daniel told me that he was pulled over to the side of the road, at exit 164A, northbound on 15. Shortly after he had pulled over,a DOT Inspector had pulled In behind him and we assume had called the Fire Department. The Fire Department was on scene and had closed down the highway pending their investigation as to what was in the trailer. Daniel advised that he would need a new wash out cap before he was able to go anywhere, and Frank Scanlan began calling various companies to try to obtain one. Daniel also advised that residue of the product had spilled down from the side of the trailer and that there was a wet spot under the trailer, but no puddles were apparent at that time. Daniel was unsure as to what the Fire Department was going to do,so I asked him to talk to them and call me back once a decision was made.  • Contacted Linda Waltonberg at Rohm and Haas in Elma,Washington. This was the company from which we picked up the product. Advised Linda of the release of product,the possible injury to a motorist, and that Emergency personnel were on scene. column168: ON 08/14/2012 AT APPROXIMATELY 0630 AM, A TRANSPORTER WAS FILLING HIS TRUCK WITH A SOLUTION OF BLEACH AT UNLOADING STATION 2 FROM A TANK AT THE SACHEM FACILITY IN CLEBURNE, TX. AFTER COMPLETING ALL THE CONNECTIONS AND PRESSURE TESTS, THE TRUCK LOADER AND A SACHEM EMPLOYEE STARTED THE LOADING PROCESS, CHECKED FOR LEAKS AND DETECTING NONE, MOVED ON TO ANOTHER UNLOADING STATION TO UNLOAD ANOTHER TRUCK.  SOMETIME DURING THE LOADING PROCESS THE PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER DROPPED CAUSING THE INTERNAL VALVE TO CLOSE. (THE VALVE CLOSURE WAS DUE TO THE DRIVER UNKNOWINGLY SHUTTING DOWN THE TRUCK ENGINE). THE HOSE THEN PULLED LOOSE FROM THE HOSE BARB ON THE HOSE FITTING, CAUSING THE BLEACH SOLUTION TO BE PUMPED FROM THE TANK INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND THEN ONTO THE GROUND OUTSIDE OF CONTAINMENT. THE TRUCK DRIVER NOTICED THE SPILL AND NOTIFIED THE TRUCK UNLOADER WHO IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE LOADING VALVES, STOPPING THE SPILL. RESPONDING ASSOCIATES WERE ABLE TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL BY DIGGING A TRENCH TO DIVERT THE  MATERIAL FLOW SO THAT IT REMAINED ON-SITE AND ALL OF THE BLEACH WAS RECOVERED AND THE AFFECTED SOIL REMOVED WITHIN 2 HOURS.
column169: SACHEM Plant Manager consulted with DPC Industries and Groendyke concerning incident and how to prevent future occurrences. Bleach truck drivers and SACHEM truck loader now have checklist that must be followed prior to loading a bleach truck and information concerning hose inspection. Also, SACHEM has purchased new hoses that will only be used on bleach trucks instead of transporter hoses.

column168: Aloha Petroleum recently experienced 2 spills at the same location. August 13, 2012 approximately at 9 am Monday morning, Aloha Petroleum truck #19215 operated by Paul Bega was filling the Honolulu Disposal above-ground storage  tank with diesel. During the delivery the driver reported a spill to Aloha's dispatch office. The driver stated the hose cam-locks at the connection point on the truck disconnected. The driver shut the pump off but not before 93 gallons of diesel spilled. Coastal Industrial Services was notified by Aloha's dispatch and they responded to the spill. 93 gallons of diesel spilled was cleaned up using oil absorbent material, the waste was placed in 55-gallon drums and will be properly disposed of. Aloha notified the National Response Center, Hawaii HEER Office and the Local Emergency Planning Committee. Honolulu Disposal EPA ID# HIP 000 141 291 is located at 1169 Mikole Street, Honolulu, Hawaii 96819.  August 17, 2012 approximately at 6 am Friday morning, Aloha Petroleum truck #19215 operated by Art Rabago was filling the same diesel tank at Honolulu Disposal. The driver reported a spill had occurred to Aloha's dispatch office. The driver stated the hose cam-locks at the connection point on the truck disconnected. Dispatch called Aloha's clean up contractor Coastal Industrial Services. Coastal responded and cleaned up the 34 gallons of diesel. Aloha Petroleum notified the National Response Center and was assigned incident number 1021351. Hawaii HEER Office and the Local Emergency Planning Committee were also notified.  When truck 19215 returned to the terminal, Aloha had the mechanic check the vehicle's pumping system. Truck 19215 is equipped with a boost system that increases the pumping rate from 85 GPM to 110 GPM. The mechanic stated the boost system is operating normally and the hose cam-locks were only slightly worn. Aloha sent the mechanic to Honolulu Disposal to inspect the above-ground storage tank.  The mechanic inspected the tank and tested the tanks delivery system. He found the diesel tank venting system was blocked.
column169: The root cause of both spills is a combination of a blocked vent and a booster pump that created excessive back pressure on the hose and caused the cam-locks to disconnect. To correct the problem and prevent future occurrences, Aloha replaced the cam-locks on the hose and disconnected the booster pump on the truck. Aloha cleared the blocked vent on the Honolulu Disposal diesel tank.    Please feel  free to contact  me at (808) 522-9714 or by email at rconner@aloha gas.com if you have any question or I may help in any other way.

column168: WHILE LOADING EAF DUST AT BAGHOUSE #1, OUR DRIVER, FRANK C. GOSS, DID NOT PULL BACK HIS TRAILER FAR ENOUGH TO THE CHUTE THAT LOADS THE DUST FROM THE SILO. MR. GOSS STATES THAT HE MISS IT BY ABOUT ONE FOOT. THEREFORE, WHEN HE LOADED THE TRAILER, SOME OF THE EAF DUST MISSED THE TRAILER AND SPILLED ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE SCALE. MR. GOSS STATES THAT HE CALLED MR. JOE BEERBOWER OF SDI AND POWER CLEAN INDUSTRIAL IMMEDIATELY. MR. GOSS STATES THAT HE CLEANED OFF HIS TRAILER THE BEST THAT HE COULD AND PROCEEDED TO BAGHOUSE #2 TO LOAD MORE DUST.  WHILE DRIVING FROM BAGHOUSE #1 TO BAGHOUSE #2, EXCESS EAF DUST FROM THE TRAILER SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY, APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS. WHEN MR. GOSS GOT TO BAGHOUSE #2, HE DID NOT UNROLL HIS TARP BEFORE UNLOADING. THEREFORE, WHEN HE LOADED, THE EAF DUST LOADED ON TOP OF THE TARP AND SPILLED ONTO THE SCALE. ACCORDING TO MR. GOSS, HE IS USED TO LOADING DUMP TRAILERS WHERE HE ONLY HAS TO PULL A FLAP ON THE TARP (PICO HOLES) AND NOT UNROLL THE ENTIRE TARP.  MR. GOSS, WHO HAS DRIVEN FOR THIS ORGANIZATION FOR OVER TWENTY SIX YEARS, ADMITTED THAT HE IS TOTALLY AT FAULT FOR THIS SPILL. HE HAS BEEN A MODEL DRIVER OVER THE YEARS AND FEELS EMBARRASSED ABOUT THESE TWO MISTAKES AND HAS NO EXCUSE.  EVEN WITH HIS EXCELLENT TRACK RECORD, HE WAS DISCIPLINED FOR THESE MISTAKES.  ALL SPILL AREAS WERE CONTAINED AND DECONTAMINATED BY POWER CLEAN. TRAFFIC WAS DIVERTED ON THE ROADWAY IN THE FACILITY UNTIL THE ROADWAY WAS CLEANED. PER SDI, THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SHIPPED AS A CONSOLIDATED SHIPMENT TO HORSEHEAD CORPORATION IN CHICAGO, IL (UHWM 006589921-ENCLOSED).
column169: ALL BMC DRIVERS WILL BE TRAINED TO GET OUT OF THEIR TRACTORS TO MAKE SURE THAT THE CHUTE IS PROPERLY ALIGNED WITH THE TRAILER BEFORE THEY PUSH THE BUTTON TO LOAD THE EAF DUST INTO THE TRAILER PROPERLY. IF THEY NEED TO MOVE THE TRACTOR/TRAILER FORWARD OR BACKWARD, THEY NEED TO DO SO.    ALSO, ALL BMC DRIVERS WILL NEED TO BE RETRAINED ON PROPERLY UNROLLING THEIR TARP WHEN THE LOAD THE EAF DUST AT SDI.

column168: ON THE DATE OF THE INCIDENT, THE MARTIN OPERATOR WAS PREPARING TO OFF-LOAD AN ASPHALT TRUCK, AT THE NEARBY LOADING RACK, INTO TANK 23 (SEE FIGURE 1). HOWEVER, WHEN THE PUMP WAS SWITCHED ON, THE OPERATOR FAILED TO REALIZE THAT THE ROUTING SWITCH WAS SET TO TANK 12, WHICH AT THE TIME WAS APPROXIMATELY "2 FEET OUT" (WITHIN 2 FEET OF ITS FULL CAPACITY). AS THE OFF-LOADING CONTINUED, THE ASPHALT EXTENDER IN TANK 12 OVERFILLED AND BEGAN LEAKING OUT ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE FROM WHERE THE OFF-LOAD OPERATOR WAS MANNING THE RACK.  A SEPARATE MARTIN EMPLOYEE NOTICED THE PRODUCT POURING OVER THE TOP OF TANK 12 AND MADE A RADIO CALL IMMEDIATELY TO SHUTOFF THE PUMP. APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND AND INTO THE DRAINAGE FOR THE IN-HOUSE WASTEWATER SYSTEM (SEE FIGURE 2).  ONCE THE SOURCE OF THE SPILL WAS STOPPED, THE FACILITY MANAGER THEN NOTIFIED A MARTIN ENVIRONMENTAL STAFF MEMBER, WHO MADE THE SPILL NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTEL ON AUGUST 29, 2012, AT APPROXIMATELY 19:00.  ASPHALT THAT COLLECTED ON THE DRAINAGE CULVERT WATERS WAS COLLECT UTILIZING BOOMS, SORBENT PADS, AND HAY. REMEDIATION OF THE PRODUCT ON THE SOIL WAS COMPLETED UTILIZING HAND SHOVELS, WHICH WERE CARRIED TO FRONT-END LOADERS. THE ASPHALT AND DIRT ULTIMATELY ENDED-UP IN A ROLL-OFF DUMPSTER LOCATED AT THE SOUTH END OF THE SITE. THEN TRANSPORTED TO SEABREEZE ENVIRONMENTAL LANDFILL ON SEPTEMBER 18, 2012. APPROX. 10 CU. YDS. (50%) OF THE ROLLOFF BOX WERE MATERIALS FROM THE RELEASE (SEE ATTACHED DISPOSAL RECORD).
column169: NOTE TO PART III, #25 NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE WAS NOTED, THIS WAS AN OPERATIONAL/PROCEDURAL FAILURE BY PERSONNEL ON DUTY.    MARTIN HAS CONDUCTED RETRAINING OF THE OPERATOR INVOLVED IN THE TANK 12 TRUCK OFF-LOADING INCIDENT. A REDUNDANCY STEP THAT IS PRESENT IN THE OPERATING PROTOCOLS REGARDING OFF-LOADING INTO TANKS WAS NOT FOLLOWED. THE OPERATIONS MANUAL CALLS FOR THE OPERATOR TO LISTEN AND/OR OBSERVE THAT THE OFF-LOADED PRODUCT HAS BEEN ROUTED TO THE CORRECT TANK. THIS STEP WAS NOT FOLLOWED FOR OFF-LOADING TO TANK 23 AND THE PRODUCT MISTAKENLY WOUND-UP GOING INTO TANK 12.    ALL MARTIN ASPHALT COMPANY OPERATORS SHALL BE RETRAINED TO THOROUGHLY FOLLOW THESE PROCEDURES. CHECKING THE DAILY TANK GAUGE RECORDS AND/OR WITH THE SHIFT SUPERVISOR SHALL BE ENCOURAGE TO ASSURE THE BEST CANDIDATE TANK IS SELECTED FOR OFF-LOADING.  MARTIN BELIEVES THAT THE QUALITY ASSURANCE AND CONTROL (QA/QC) AFFORDED BY THE REDUNDANCY STEPS SHALL PREVENT FUTURE RELEASES OF THIS NATURE.

column168: AT 1300 ON 08/15/12 OUR LAWN SPRAY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING EAST-BOUND ON ATLANTIC BLVD AT 35 MPH. DRAINAGE DAMS AND SOAK UP WERE USE TO CONTROL THE SPILLAGE. FIFTY GALLON OF MIXED PRODUCT CONTAINED 4 OUNCES OF BIFEN. column168: On the morning of 8/24/2012, I was assigned a split load of diesel and gasoline to be delivered to the City of Mentor Department of Public Works. I loaded the product and arrived on-scene at approximately 0905 hrs. Upon entering the properly, I proceeded to the superintendants office and took an electronic tank level reading from the veeder root system there. After, I continued on around the yard and set up my truck and trailer to the south of the on-site tanks for off loading. I sat in my truck and studied the tank readings along with the order amounts I was given. I knew that I had wanted to offload the 2800 gallon compartment of gasoline (E-87) on my truck first into tank three on site. I exited my truck and connected all fittings and hoses and began my off load. I checked to see that everything was operating properly and entered my truck to do the paperwork for the delivery.    When the compartment emptied, I exited my truck and walked around the truck to find a Mentor city employee coming my way shouting that the product had begun to come out of the top of the tank and was spilling upon the ground on the opposite side of where I was offloading. I apparently had hooked to the wrong tank and assumed reading left to right that tank three was to the right of them. I immediately shut off the compartment and ran around to the cab of the truck to shut down the pump system. I then ran around the tanks and we began opening spill kits to try and block the fuel from entering the storm drain located on the backside of the tanks. I ran to my truck and grabbed as many absorbent pads as I could and ran back. Numerous employees then began running up with a pig pads (absorbent pads) and sand bags and eventually other employees came over with a tow motor containing numerous bags of oil dry and they were spread thoughout the area. The fire department and Mike Grummitt were notified immediately. It was determined that roughly 200 gallons of product had been lost.    The fire department arrived on scene and traced the storm drain on the property to a retention basin located at the northeast corner of the property and check for contamination in the pond. There was very little and to be precautionary, they put up an absorbent barrier around the outlet. The EPA was notified along with inland Waters for cleanup. Members from the Lubrizol fire department showed up around 1040 and it was determined for best interest to insert and inflatable plug into the drainage line to deter and possible contamination to which they did.    EPA officials arrived on the scene to evaluate the situation and it was determined that the situation had been handled quite well and no product had made its way off of the premises. Safety Officer Ray Lipa from Great lakes Petroleum showed up to evaluate and document the situation. Just after 1200 hrs, members of inland waters arrived on site and began cleanup. A vac truck was used to skim the product off of the top of the standing water in the s
column169: For all intensive purposes, this was an accident. There was no malice or dereliction of duty involved. It was simple mistake of blind fill tanks that have neither outside way of reading them nor a way of sticking them for volume. They neither have catch areas for spills nor alarms to notify that the tank was being overfilled.    Operator instructed per his training to always stick the tanks before offloading and to never as per his training to always remain at point of fill until complete. We are currently reviewing all training associated with this incident/action to see what additional training can be done to prevent future incidents.

AT 0324 HRS ON 8/28/2012, THE OPENING CREW HAD COMPLETED THE QA PROCESS AND ALL THE BELLY VALVES ON ALL THE CARS WERE IN THE OPEN POSITION. AT 0500 HRS, A KM EE, WHO WAS ON THE FIRE WATCH/TRACK CHECK COULD SMELL ETHANOL. HE WAS ON TRACK 5 NEAR SPOT 18 AT THE TIME. HE WALKED DOWN TO TRACK 5 SPOT 24 (LAST CAR ON TRACK 5) AND AS HE NEARED THE CAR, HE COULD SEE THE ETHANOL SLOWLY BUBBLING OUT OF THE OPEN MANWAY COVER. (THE COVER IS LEFT OPEN A COUPLE INCHES TO ALLOW AIRE TO ENTER THE CAR AND PREVENT CAR FROM IMPLODING). HE WAS NOT IMMEDIATELY ABLE TO GET CLOSE ENOUGH TO THE CAR TO CLOSE THE BELLY VALVE OR MANWAY VALVE (DUE TO ETHANOL RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF CAR). WHEN THE ETHANOL BUBBLING OUT OF THE MANWAY SLOWED, HE CLOSED THE MANFOLD VALVE.    HE LEFT THE VALVE IN THE OFF POSITION FOR APPROX 5 MIN, THEN SLOWLY BEGAN OPENING THE VALVE AND MONITORING THE SITE GLASS TO VERIFY THE PRODUCT WAS MOVING IN THE CORRECT DIRECTION AND NOT BACK FLOWING INTO THE CAR.    IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROX 40-50 GALLONS WERE RELEASED FROM THE MANWAY. OF THAT 40-50 GALLONS, IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 30 GALLONS LANDED INSIDE THE DRIP PAN, 5 GALLONS MADE IT TO THE CONCRETE AREA AND APPROX 10-15 GALLONS MADE IT WAY TO THE BALLAST AREA UNDER THE CAR.
column169: AFTER INVESTIGATING THIS RELEASE, WE EXAMINED POTENTIAL MEANS OF ELIMINATING AIR FROM TRAVELING BACK THROUGH THE MANIFOLD LINES ANY UP THROUGH THE RAILCAR. WE HAD PREVIOUSLY INSTALLED 8 TRAIL CHECK VALVES AT VARIOUS LOCATIONS AT UNLOADING SITE TO DETERMINE IF THEY WOULD IMPEDE THE UNLOADING OPERATION. ONCE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VALVES DID NOT NEGATIVELY AFFECT THE OPERATION, 76 MORE CHECK VALVES WERE ORDERED. THE VALVES ARRIVED ON 8/27/12 AND WERE INSTALLED ON 8/29/12.

column168: On 08/16/2012 around 2125 one of the out bound dock workers was reworking a trailer, he pulled a pallet out of the trailer that had the pro in question sitting on top of the pallet.  The box fell off the pallet and underneath the pallet causing the glass container inside of the box to break allowing the product to spill out.      Another employee turned around to see what had happen and as he was walking off the dock stand he inhaled some of the vapors that were coming off of the box.  He than in turned called supervisor on the radio and asked for help down on the out bound in.  As supervisor got down there he pointed out the box and the reddish orange vapor that was coming out of it.  He informed me that it was a strong odor and that he had inhaled some of it.  Asked if he was ok and we than proceeded to close off the area surrounding the box.      We found the BOL and I went into the office to call chemtrec, safety, and the fire department, after calling everyone I did a 3 way conference call with safety and Safety Manager.  At this time exposed employee was out with the fire department and supervisor was finishing up the phone call with safety.      Employee was treated by an Aid unit at the insistence of the fire department, he declined to go to the hospital.  The fire department put the remains of the product in an over pack drum and placed it into os&d, supervisor to do the spill report by the end of shift, there where no pictures as it was unsafe to be around the product while it was having a chemical reaction....

APPROXIMATELY 15:15, DRIVER PICKED UP AT ROYAL CHEMICAL. ARRIVED AT COSIGNEE AT 15:45. WALKED TO GUARD HOUSE TO CHECK-IN, AND WENT BACK TO TRUCK. AT THAT TIME, NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING OUT OF NOSE OF TRAILER. CONTACTED UNLOADING CLERK AND COCA COLA BOTTLING RESPONSE TEAM. PUT DOWN ABSORBENT SOCKS AND ALL-ABSORBENT MATERIAL. DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH OFFICE. DISPATCH OFFICE CONTACTED ROCHEM CORPORATION AND SPOKE TO PATRICIA O'BRIAN AT APPROXIMATELY 16:00. SHE CONTACTED PATRICK O'BRIAN. MT PLEASANT TRANSFER CONTACTED ROYAL CHEMICAL AT 16:00 ALSO. PER MT.PLEASANT TRANSFER'S DRIVER, COCA COLA CONTACTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. THE RESPONSE TEAM CAME OUT AND TOOK OVER. AT APPROXIMATELY 21:50 RESPONSE TEAM HAD FINISHED CLEAN UP.  COCA COLA TRANSFERRED ONE TOTE INTO TWO TOTES. THE ONE TOTE THAT FAILED, COCA COLA TOOK OFF AT THEIR SITE. THE REMAINING FOUR TOTES MT PLEASANT TRANSFER TOOK BACK TO ROYAL CHEMICAL ON THE MORNING OF 08/3/2012.
column169: OUR QUESTION TO ROYAL CHEMICAL/ROCHEM WAS WHAT THE MANUFACTURER DATE AND LAST TEST OF IBC TOTES. NO INFORMATION WAS FURNISHED TO MT. PLEASANT TRANSFER. ROYAL CHEMICAL/ROCHEM DECIDED TO USE OTHER CARRIERS.

AT ABOUT 22:45 ON 8/23/12 I WAS HOME WHEN I GOT A CALL FROM FRANKLIN BLOUNT THAT ADAM HAD JUST HAD A MAJOR SPILL AT EMSERCO TRENTON FACILITY. I ASKED HIM TO RUN OVER THERE AS HE WAS MUCH CLOSER THAN GREGG THE NIGHT SHIFT LEAD DRIVER. FRANKLIN THEN CALLED ME BACK ABOUT 1/2 HOUR LATER AND CONFIRMED THAT IT WAS INDEED A VERY LARGE SPILL (APPROX 10 BBLS). I DIRECTED FRANKLIN AND ADAM TO SECURE THE AREA AND HELP DIRECT THE TRUCK TRAFFIC AROUND THE AREA UNTIL I WAS ABLE TO GET ON SCENE. AT THAT TIME THERE WAS NO STANDING OIL ON THE GROUND THAT COULD BE EITHER SUCKED UP OR SOAKED UP AS IT HAD ALL ABSORBED INTO THE GROUND. I THEN CALLED ROB ELMORE OF FALCO THAT OPERATES THE FACILITY AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SPILL AND PROCEEDED TO THE LOCATION. UPON ARRIVING AND INSPECTING THE SPILL (ABOUT 2:00 AM ON 8/24) THERE WAS NOTHING WE COULD DO UNTIL DAYLIGHT SO WE WAITED UNTIL ROB ARRIVED ON LOCATION ABOUT 7:00 AM. I DID TALK WITH ADAM AT THAT POINT TO FIND OUT THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT. HE INFORMED THAT HE HAD CHECKED THE TANK LEVELS, HOOKED UP HIS HOSE AND BEGAN UNLOADING, SIGNED INTO THE LOG IN THE SHACK AND THEN WENT TO THE CAB OF HIS TRUCK TO ATTEND TO SOME PAPERWORK. THIS IS AGAINST OUR COMPANY POLICY. THE DRIVERS SHOULD ALWAYS ATTEND TO THEIR VALVES WHILE LOADING AND UNLOADING. ADAM ADMITTED TO NOT FOLLOWING PROCEDURE AT THAT TIME.    WHEN ROB ARRIVED WE DISCUSSED THE OPTIONS FOR CLEANUP AND CONTACTED JMAC AND BEGAN THE PAPERWORK PROCESS SO THAT THEY COULD EXCAVATE AND PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE CONTAMINATED DIRT. WE ALSO HAD ADAM DRUG TESTED AT THAT TIME AS IS COMPANY POLICY.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.
